{"title_page": "Cheryl Derricotte", "text_new": "[[File:Artist Cheryl P. Derricotte.jpg|thumb|Derricotte]]\n'''Cheryl Patrice Derricotte'''  is an American visual artist  working mostly with glass and paper. She lives and works in [[San Francisco|San Francisco, CA]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nDerricotte is originally from [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, DC]].\n\nShe holds a Master of Fine Arts from the [[California Institute of Integral Studies]] (CIIS),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ciis.edu/academics/integral-teaching-fellowship/itf-fellows-and-mentors/cheryl-derricotte|title=Cheryl Derricotte|last=|first=|date=|website=CALIFORNIA INSTITUTE OF INTEGRAL STUDIES|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> a Master of Regional Planning from [[Cornell University]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artpractical.com/archive/contributor/cheryl-patrice-derricotte/|title=Cheryl Patrice Derricotte|last=Addy|website=Art Practical|language=en|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> and a B.A. in Urban Affairs from [[Barnard College]], [[Columbia University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/03/23/Black-students-at-Columbia-University-threatened-Monday-to-sue/6949543474000/|title=Black students at Columbia University threatened Monday to sue...|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\n== Artwork ==\nDerricotte describes her artwork process as:<blockquote>Identities shaped by home (or homelessness); natural beauty (or disasters), memories of happiness (or loss) inspire my artwork. This results in works on glass and paper.  Both materials are translucent and seemingly fragile, yet they are hearty enough to survive the passage of time between civilizations.\n\nI make art from research. This type of inquiry also leads me not just to economic but also environmental concerns. Observations of current events, politics, and urban landscapes are my entry into these issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.berkeleypubliclibrary.org/events/cheryl-derricotte-ghostsships-images-slavery-captured-glass-central|title=Cheryl Derricotte: Ghosts/Ships: Images of Slavery Rendered in Glass @Central {{!}} Berkeley Public Library|website=www.berkeleypubliclibrary.org|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nShe has exhibited in galleries,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loyola.edu/academics/fine-arts/gallery/past|title=Past Exhibitions - Julio Fine Arts Gallery - Department of Fine Arts - Loyola University Maryland|website=www.loyola.edu|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> museums and art spaces. Her first solo exhibition in 2016, ''Ghosts/Ships,'' held at the Museum of the African Diaspora in San Francisco, \"offers a glimpse into the global African slave trade that is both subtle and direct in its links between past and present.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/11324874/cheryl-derricotte-mines-the-museum-for-haunting-images-of-slave-trade|title=Cheryl Derricotte Mines the Museum for Haunting Images of Slave Trade|date=2016-02-17|website=KQED|language=en-us|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> In 2019 she was part of the \u201cAncestral Journeys\u201d exhibition at the [[Euphrat Museum of Art]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.deanza.edu/euphrat/exhibitions.html|title=In the Museum|date=2019-10-23|website=DeAnza College|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref> an exhibition which \"spotlights self-identity, family history, immigration, and diasporas...\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lavozdeanza.com/features/campus-beat/2019/02/19/ancestral-journeys-showcases-immigration-stories/|title=\u2018Ancestral Journeys\u2019 showcases immigration stories|last=Sun|first=Yami|date=2019-02-19|website=La Voz News|access-date=2019-04-11}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nHer awards include a San Francisco Individual Artist Commission; Hemera Foundation Tending Space Fellowship for Artists; the Rick and Val Beck Scholarship for Glass;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artpractical.com/column/episode-2-cheryl-derricotte-and-angela-hennessy/|title=Episode 2: Cheryl Derricotte and Angela Hennessy|last=Hennessy|first=Angela|website=Art Practical|language=en|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> Emerging Artist at the Museum of the African Diaspora;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moadsf.org/exhibition/ghostsships/|title=Ghosts/Ships|website=MoAD Museum of African Diaspora|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> Gardarev Center Fellow;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gardarev.org/directions/fellows-in-the-news/|title=Fellows in the News {{!}} The Gardarev Center|website=gardarev.org|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> Art Alliance for Contemporary Glass\u2019 Visionary Scholarship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://contempglass.org/about/visionary-scholarship-fund|title=Visionary Scholarship Fund {{!}} AACG|last=|first=|date=|website=Art Alliance for Contemporary Art|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> and a D.C. Commission on the Arts & Humanities/ National Endowment for the Arts Artist Fellowship Grant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gardarev.org/about/fellow-bios/|title=Fellow Bios {{!}} The Gardarev Center|website=gardarev.org|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> She was a Finalist for the LEAP Award in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://contemporarycraft.org/cherylderricotte/|title=Cheryl Derricotte \u2013 2016 LEAP Finalist on Contemporary Craft|last=Craft|first=Contemporary|website=Contemporary Craft|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\n== Arts Activist ==\nDerricotte is the currentSecretary/The Minister of Information for Three Point Nine Art Collective,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://threepointninecollective.art/|title=Three Point Nine Collective|last=|first=|date=|website=Three Point Nine Collective Art|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://openspace.sfmoma.org/author/3point9collective/|title=On San Francisco and Ownership: The 3.9 Art Collective Responds|website=Open Space|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> a group of San Francisco area Black artists.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vessel-gallery.com/online-events/2020/3/19/artist-talk-migration-cheryl-derricotte|title=Artist Talk {{!}} MIGRATION {{!}} Cheryl Derricotte|website=Vessel Gallery|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> She is also the Chief Mindfulness Officer of Crux,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crux.black/|title=Crux|website=Crux|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> a U.S. nationwide cooperative of Black artists \"working at the intersection of art and technology through immersive storytelling (Virtual Reality).\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Cheryl Derricotte}}\n* [http://cherylderricotte.com/ Cheryl Derricotte Website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Derricote, Cheryl}}\n[[Category:20th-century American printmakers]]\n[[Category:Artists from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:African-American contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:African-American culture]]\n[[Category:21st-century American printmakers]]\n[[Category:20th-century African-American people]]\n[[Category:Glass artists]]\n[[Category:Women glass artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:African-American women artists]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:Barnard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Artist Cheryl P. Derricotte.jpg|thumb|Derricotte]]\n'''Cheryl Patrice Derricotte'''  is an American visual artist  working mostly with glass and paper. She lives and works in [[San Francisco|San Francisco, CA]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nDerricotte is originally from [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, DC]].\n\nShe holds a Master of Fine Arts from the [[California Institute of Integral Studies]] (CIIS),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ciis.edu/academics/integral-teaching-fellowship/itf-fellows-and-mentors/cheryl-derricotte|title=Cheryl Derricotte|last=|first=|date=|website=CALIFORNIA INSTITUTE OF INTEGRAL STUDIES|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> a Master of Regional Planning from [[Cornell University]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artpractical.com/archive/contributor/cheryl-patrice-derricotte/|title=Cheryl Patrice Derricotte|last=Addy|website=Art Practical|language=en|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> and a B.A. in Urban Affairs from [[Barnard College]], [[Columbia University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/03/23/Black-students-at-Columbia-University-threatened-Monday-to-sue/6949543474000/|title=Black students at Columbia University threatened Monday to sue...|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\n== Artwork ==\nDerricotte describes her artwork process as:<blockquote>Identities shaped by home (or homelessness); natural beauty (or disasters), memories of happiness (or loss) inspire my artwork. This results in works on glass and paper.  Both materials are translucent and seemingly fragile, yet they are hearty enough to survive the passage of time between civilizations.\n\nI make art from research. This type of inquiry also leads me not just to economic but also environmental concerns. Observations of current events, politics, and urban landscapes are my entry into these issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.berkeleypubliclibrary.org/events/cheryl-derricotte-ghostsships-images-slavery-captured-glass-central|title=Cheryl Derricotte: Ghosts/Ships: Images of Slavery Rendered in Glass @Central {{!}} Berkeley Public Library|website=www.berkeleypubliclibrary.org|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nShe has exhibited in galleries,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loyola.edu/academics/fine-arts/gallery/past|title=Past Exhibitions - Julio Fine Arts Gallery - Department of Fine Arts - Loyola University Maryland|website=www.loyola.edu|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> museums and art spaces. Her first solo exhibition in 2016, ''Ghosts/Ships,'' held at the Museum of the African Diaspora in San Francisco, \"offers a glimpse into the global African slave trade that is both subtle and direct in its links between past and present.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/11324874/cheryl-derricotte-mines-the-museum-for-haunting-images-of-slave-trade|title=Cheryl Derricotte Mines the Museum for Haunting Images of Slave Trade|date=2016-02-17|website=KQED|language=en-us|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> In 2019 she was part of the \u201cAncestral Journeys\u201d exhibition at the [[Euphrat Museum of Art]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.deanza.edu/euphrat/exhibitions.html|title=In the Museum|date=2019-10-23|website=DeAnza College|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref> an exhibition which \"spotlights self-identity, family history, immigration, and diasporas...\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lavozdeanza.com/features/campus-beat/2019/02/19/ancestral-journeys-showcases-immigration-stories/|title=\u2018Ancestral Journeys\u2019 showcases immigration stories|last=Sun|first=Yami|date=2019-02-19|website=La Voz News|access-date=2019-04-11}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nHer awards include a San Francisco Individual Artist Commission; Hemera Foundation Tending Space Fellowship for Artists; the Rick and Val Beck Scholarship for Glass;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artpractical.com/column/episode-2-cheryl-derricotte-and-angela-hennessy/|title=Episode 2: Cheryl Derricotte and Angela Hennessy|last=Hennessy|first=Angela|website=Art Practical|language=en|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> Emerging Artist at the Museum of the African Diaspora;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moadsf.org/exhibition/ghostsships/|title=Ghosts/Ships|website=MoAD Museum of African Diaspora|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> Gardarev Center Fellow;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gardarev.org/directions/fellows-in-the-news/|title=Fellows in the News {{!}} The Gardarev Center|website=gardarev.org|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> Art Alliance for Contemporary Glass\u2019 Visionary Scholarship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://contempglass.org/about/visionary-scholarship-fund|title=Visionary Scholarship Fund {{!}} AACG|last=|first=|date=|website=Art Alliance for Contemporary Art|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> and a D.C. Commission on the Arts & Humanities/ National Endowment for the Arts Artist Fellowship Grant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gardarev.org/about/fellow-bios/|title=Fellow Bios {{!}} The Gardarev Center|website=gardarev.org|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> She was a Finalist for the LEAP Award in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://contemporarycraft.org/cherylderricotte/|title=Cheryl Derricotte \u2013 2016 LEAP Finalist on Contemporary Craft|last=Craft|first=Contemporary|website=Contemporary Craft|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Cheryl Derricotte}}\n* [http://cherylderricotte.com/ Cheryl Derricotte Website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Derricote, Cheryl}}\n[[Category:20th-century American printmakers]]\n[[Category:Artists from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:African-American contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:African-American culture]]\n[[Category:21st-century American printmakers]]\n[[Category:20th-century African-American people]]\n[[Category:Glass artists]]\n[[Category:Women glass artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:African-American women artists]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:Barnard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Artdoofus", "label": "safe", "comment": "Expansion and update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cheryl_Derricotte"}
{"title_page": "Sofia Wylie", "text_new": "{{Short description|American actress and dancer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = \n| image              = Sofia Wylie, Milana Vayntrub & Kathreen Khavari (47531922961) (cropped).jpg.png\n| caption            = Wylie at the 2019 [[WonderCon]]\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|2004|1|7}}\n| birth_place        = [[Scottsdale, Arizona]], U.S.\n| residence          = \n| othername          = \n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n*Actress\n*dancer\n}}\n| yearsactive        = 2011\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Sofia Wylie''' (born January 7, 2004)<ref name=\"DisneyABCPress-Andi Mack-Bios\">{{cite web|title=Disney Channel - Andi Mack - Show Bios (Sofia Wylie)|url=http://www.disneyabcpress.com/disneychannel/shows/andi-mack/bios/|website=Disney ABC Press|accessdate=July 15, 2017}}</ref> is an American actress and dancer. She gained prominence through her main role as Buffy Driscoll on the [[Disney Channel]] series ''[[Andi Mack]]''. Her other roles include Cory Bailey in the 2019 film ''[[Back of the Net]]'', [[Ironheart (character)|Riri Williams]] in the ''[[Marvel Rising]]'' animated franchise, Mia Brooks in the Disney web series ''[[Shook (web series)|Shook]]''  and Gina Porter in the [[Disney+]] series ''[[High School Musical: The Musical: The Series]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nWylie was born in Wuhan, China and grew up in Beijing to parents Chris and Amy.<ref name=\"anthem news\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anthemnews.com/sofia-wylie-disney-kid/|title=Sofia Wylie is a Disney Kid Now|journal=Anthem News|date=20 September 2016|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref> She has an older sister, Isabella \"Bella\", who appeared in an episode of ''[[Chopped Junior]]'' and won.<ref name=\"wylie sisters\">{{cite web|url=https://www.lucamagazine.com/the-wylie-sisters/|title=Believe...The Wylie Sisters|journal=Luca Magazine|date=2016|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref> Wylie has been dancing since she was 5 years old<ref name=\"wylie sisters\"/> and trained in acting at Second City Training Center in Hollywood, California.<ref name=\"DisneyABCPress-Andi Mack-Bios\"/> She is a quarter [[Korean ethnicity|Korean]] on her father\u2019s side.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/sofiawylie/status/870976204492361729|title=I love K-pop  yes I am part Korean|last=Wylie|first=Sofia|date=2017-06-03|website=Twitter|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nWylie started her career in dance, making appearances on ''[[So You Think You Can Dance (U.S. TV series)|So You Think You Can Dance]]'' in 2011 and 2016 and ''[[America's Got Talent]]'' in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dancespirit.com/sofia-wylie-disney-channel-star-2524962250.html|title=Talking with Disney Channel Star and Dance Dynamo Sofia Wylie|last=Beard|first=Katherine|journal=Dance Spirit|date=26 January 2018|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref> She performed on [[Justin Bieber]]'s ''[[Purpose World Tour]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/disney-star-sofia-wylie-keeps-grounded-by-family-in-an-industry-where-fame-can-change-a-person/news-story/4a31cd47a7224fa8b31ac1f03b0c3a59|title=Disney star Sofia Wylie keeps grounded by family in an industry where fame can change a person|last=Moran|first=Jonathon|journal=The Daily Telegraph|date=7 May 2018|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"instyle 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.instyle.com/news/sofia-wylie-justin-bieber-zendaya|title=Disney's 14-Year-old Breakout Star Has Danced for Bieber and Might Be the Next Zendaya|last=Simon|first=Samantha|date=8 March 2018|accessdate=12 February 2019|journal=InStyle}}</ref> In 2017, she started the Internet-based 4K Dance Series with Utah dancers while filming ''[[Andi Mack]]''.<ref name=\"instyle 1\"/> In 2019, she started ''Dancing with Sofia Wylie'', an [[IGTV]] educational dance series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tigerbeat.com/2019/03/dancing-with-sofia-wylie/|title=Sofia Wylie Debuts New IGTV Series 'Dancing With Sofia Wylie'|journal=TigerBeat|first=Shelby|last=Stivale|date=March 12, 2019|accessdate=June 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, it was announced that Wylie would star in her first major acting role as Buffy Driscoll, a main character and one of Andi's best friends on the Disney Channel series ''[[Andi Mack]]''.<ref name=\"anthem news\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.laughingplace.com/w/news/2016/09/07/disney-channels-andi-mack-begins-production/|title=Disney Channel\u2019s Andi Mack Begins Production|journal=Laughing Place|date=7 September 2016|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref> Wylie made her film debut as Cory Bailey in the 2019 Australian film, ''[[Back of the Net]]'',<ref name=\"botn 1\"/> which had a theatrical release in Australia and aired on [[Disney Channel]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.j-14.com/posts/sofia-wylie-will-star-in-disney-channel-original-movie-back-of-the-net/|title=Get Ready: A Movie Starring Sofia Wylie Is Coming to Disney Channel, And We Have the Deets|journal=J-14|first=Jordyn|last=Tilchin|date=May 21, 2019|accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref> Wylie debuted her first single, \"Side by Side\", for ''[[Marvel Rising]]: Chasing Ghosts'' in January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8493947/sofia-wylie-side-by-side-video|title=Disney & Marvel Star Sofia Wylie Makes Her Music Debut With 'Side by Side': Premiere|journal=Billboard|first=Jeff|last=Benjamin|date=January 18, 2019|accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> She voiced the role of [[Riri Williams]] in animated TV movie, ''[[Marvel Rising]]: Heart of Iron'', which aired on [[Disney XD]].<ref name=\"hoi 1\"/> She reprised the role for ''[[Marvel Rising]]: Battle of the Bands'' and in season 3 of ''[[Spider-Man: Maximum Venom]]''.\n\nOn February 15, 2019, Wylie was cast as Gina Porter in the [[Disney+]] series, ''[[High School Musical: The Musical: The Series]]'', which was available from launch that November.<ref name=\"hsm announcement\"/> It was announced in August that Wylie would star as Mia in ''Shook'', a short-form web series premiering on [[Disney Channel]]'s [[YouTube]] channel in September.<ref name=\"shook announcement\"/>\n\nIn March 2019, Wylie launched a production company, AIFOS<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/disney-channel-sofia-wylie-aifos-productions-company-1202570845/|title=Disney Channel Star Sofia Wylie Launches AIFOS Productions Company|last=Amanda|first=N'Duka|journal=Deadline|date=6 March 2019|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref> and is set to adapt Jenny Torres Sanchez's novel, ''The Fall of Innocence,'' as its first project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thefandom.net/disney-star-options-rights-to-ya-drama-the-fall-of-innocence/|title=Disney Star Options Rights To YA Drama 'The Fall of Innocence''|journal=The Fandom|date=March 8, 2019|accessdate=June 9, 2019}}</ref> In June 2019, Wylie signed with [[United Talent Agency]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/uta-signs-disney-channel-star-sofia-wylie-1220232|title=UTA Signs Disney Channel Star Sofia Wylie (Exclusive)|journal=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Rebecca|last=Sun|date=June 20, 2019|accessdate=August 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! class=\"unsortable\" | {{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 2011, 2016 \n| ''[[So You Think You Can Dance (U.S. TV series)|So You Think You Can Dance]]'' \n| Herself \n| Dancer; 2 episodes \n|\n|-\n| 2015 \n| ''[[America's Got Talent]]'' \n| Herself \n| Dancer; 1 episode \n|\n|-\n| 2017 \n| ''[[Nicky, Ricky, Dicky & Dawn]]'' \n| June \n| 3 episodes\n| <ref name=\"DisneyABCPress-Andi Mack-Bios\"/>\n|-\n| 2017\u20132019\n| ''[[Andi Mack]]'' \n| Buffy Driscoll \n| Main role \n| <ref name=\"anthem news\"/>\n|-\n| 2019 \n| ''[[Marvel Rising]]: Heart of Iron'' \n| [[Ironheart (character)|Ironheart / Riri Williams]] \n| Voice role; television film \n| <ref name=\"hoi 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.marvel.com/articles/tv-shows/two-new-marvel-rising-animated-specials-are-coming-your-way|title=Two New 'Marvel Rising' Animated Specials Are Coming Your Way|first=Christine|last=Dinh|journal=Marvel|date=2 October 2018|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019 \n| ''[[Back of the Net]]'' \n| Cory Bailey \n| Film\n| <ref name=\"botn 1\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/andi-mack-star-sofia-wylie-scores-big-screen-role-with-australian-feature-back-of-the-net-1202354599/|title=\u2018Andi Mack\u2019 Star Sofia Wylie Scores Big Screen Role With Australian Soccer Feature \u2018Back Of The Net\u2019|first=Peter|last=White|journal=Deadline|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019 \n| ''[[Marvel Rising]]: Battle of the Bands'' \n| [[Ironheart (character)|Ironheart / Riri Williams]] \n| Voice role; special\n| \n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Shook (web series)|Shook]]'' \n| Amelia \"Mia\" Brooks\n| Web miniseries; main role\n| <ref name=\"shook announcement\">{{cite web|url=https://discussingfilm.net/2019/08/01/sofia-wylie-cast-in-shook-series-for-disney-exclusive/|title=Sofia Wylie Cast In \u2018Shook\u2019 Series For Disney+ (EXCLUSIVE)|first=Jacob|last=Fisher|journal=DiscussingFilm|date=1 August 2019|accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019\u2013present\n| ''[[High School Musical: The Musical: The Series]]'' \n| Gina Porter\n| Main role \n| <ref name=\"hsm announcement\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1015582/meet-the-cast-of-disney-s-high-school-musical-the-musical-the-series|title=Meet the Cast of Disney's High School Musical: The Musical: The Series|first=Chris|last=Harnick|journal=E! News|date=15 February 2019|accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Spider-Man: Maximum Venom]]''\n| Ironheart / Riri Williams\n| ''Upcoming'' (season 3)\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|8402202}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wylie, Sofia}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2004 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Scottsdale, Arizona]]\n[[Category:African-American child actresses]]\n[[Category:African-American female dancers]]\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:American actresses of Korean descent]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American female singers]]\n[[Category:American film production company founders]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:American web series actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American actress and dancer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = \n| image              = Sofia Wylie, Milana Vayntrub & Kathreen Khavari (47531922961) (cropped).jpg.png\n| caption            = Wylie at the 2019 [[WonderCon]]\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|2004|1|7}}\n| birth_place        = [[Scottsdale, Arizona]], U.S.\n| residence          = \n| othername          = \n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n*Actress\n*dancer\n}}\n| yearsactive        = 2011\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Sofia Wylie''' (born January 7, 2004)<ref name=\"DisneyABCPress-Andi Mack-Bios\">{{cite web|title=Disney Channel - Andi Mack - Show Bios (Sofia Wylie)|url=http://www.disneyabcpress.com/disneychannel/shows/andi-mack/bios/|website=Disney ABC Press|accessdate=July 15, 2017}}</ref> is an American actress and dancer. She gained prominence through her main role as Buffy Driscoll on the [[Disney Channel]] series ''[[Andi Mack]]''. Her other roles include Cory Bailey in the 2019 film ''[[Back of the Net]]'', [[Ironheart (character)|Riri Williams]] in the ''[[Marvel Rising]]'' animated franchise, Mia Brooks in the Disney web series ''[[Shook (web series)|Shook]]''  and Gina Porter in the [[Disney+]] series ''[[High School Musical: The Musical: The Series]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nWylie was born in Scottsdale, Arizona and grew up in Tramonto to parents Chris and Amy.<ref name=\"anthem news\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anthemnews.com/sofia-wylie-disney-kid/|title=Sofia Wylie is a Disney Kid Now|journal=Anthem News|date=20 September 2016|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref> She has an older sister, Isabella \"Bella\", who appeared in an episode of ''[[Chopped Junior]]'' and won.<ref name=\"wylie sisters\">{{cite web|url=https://www.lucamagazine.com/the-wylie-sisters/|title=Believe...The Wylie Sisters|journal=Luca Magazine|date=2016|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref> Wylie has been dancing since she was 5 years old<ref name=\"wylie sisters\"/> and trained in acting at Second City Training Center in Hollywood, California.<ref name=\"DisneyABCPress-Andi Mack-Bios\"/> She is a quarter [[Korean ethnicity|Korean]] on her father\u2019s side.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/sofiawylie/status/870976204492361729|title=I love K-pop  yes I am part Korean|last=Wylie|first=Sofia|date=2017-06-03|website=Twitter|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nWylie started her career in dance, making appearances on ''[[So You Think You Can Dance (U.S. TV series)|So You Think You Can Dance]]'' in 2011 and 2016 and ''[[America's Got Talent]]'' in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dancespirit.com/sofia-wylie-disney-channel-star-2524962250.html|title=Talking with Disney Channel Star and Dance Dynamo Sofia Wylie|last=Beard|first=Katherine|journal=Dance Spirit|date=26 January 2018|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref> She performed on [[Justin Bieber]]'s ''[[Purpose World Tour]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/disney-star-sofia-wylie-keeps-grounded-by-family-in-an-industry-where-fame-can-change-a-person/news-story/4a31cd47a7224fa8b31ac1f03b0c3a59|title=Disney star Sofia Wylie keeps grounded by family in an industry where fame can change a person|last=Moran|first=Jonathon|journal=The Daily Telegraph|date=7 May 2018|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"instyle 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.instyle.com/news/sofia-wylie-justin-bieber-zendaya|title=Disney's 14-Year-old Breakout Star Has Danced for Bieber and Might Be the Next Zendaya|last=Simon|first=Samantha|date=8 March 2018|accessdate=12 February 2019|journal=InStyle}}</ref> In 2017, she started the Internet-based 4K Dance Series with Utah dancers while filming ''[[Andi Mack]]''.<ref name=\"instyle 1\"/> In 2019, she started ''Dancing with Sofia Wylie'', an [[IGTV]] educational dance series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tigerbeat.com/2019/03/dancing-with-sofia-wylie/|title=Sofia Wylie Debuts New IGTV Series 'Dancing With Sofia Wylie'|journal=TigerBeat|first=Shelby|last=Stivale|date=March 12, 2019|accessdate=June 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, it was announced that Wylie would star in her first major acting role as Buffy Driscoll, a main character and one of Andi's best friends on the Disney Channel series ''[[Andi Mack]]''.<ref name=\"anthem news\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.laughingplace.com/w/news/2016/09/07/disney-channels-andi-mack-begins-production/|title=Disney Channel\u2019s Andi Mack Begins Production|journal=Laughing Place|date=7 September 2016|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref> Wylie made her film debut as Cory Bailey in the 2019 Australian film, ''[[Back of the Net]]'',<ref name=\"botn 1\"/> which had a theatrical release in Australia and aired on [[Disney Channel]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.j-14.com/posts/sofia-wylie-will-star-in-disney-channel-original-movie-back-of-the-net/|title=Get Ready: A Movie Starring Sofia Wylie Is Coming to Disney Channel, And We Have the Deets|journal=J-14|first=Jordyn|last=Tilchin|date=May 21, 2019|accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref> Wylie debuted her first single, \"Side by Side\", for ''[[Marvel Rising]]: Chasing Ghosts'' in January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8493947/sofia-wylie-side-by-side-video|title=Disney & Marvel Star Sofia Wylie Makes Her Music Debut With 'Side by Side': Premiere|journal=Billboard|first=Jeff|last=Benjamin|date=January 18, 2019|accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> She voiced the role of [[Riri Williams]] in animated TV movie, ''[[Marvel Rising]]: Heart of Iron'', which aired on [[Disney XD]].<ref name=\"hoi 1\"/> She reprised the role for ''[[Marvel Rising]]: Battle of the Bands'' and in season 3 of ''[[Spider-Man: Maximum Venom]]''.\n\nOn February 15, 2019, Wylie was cast as Gina Porter in the [[Disney+]] series, ''[[High School Musical: The Musical: The Series]]'', which was available from launch that November.<ref name=\"hsm announcement\"/> It was announced in August that Wylie would star as Mia in ''Shook'', a short-form web series premiering on [[Disney Channel]]'s [[YouTube]] channel in September.<ref name=\"shook announcement\"/>\n\nIn March 2019, Wylie launched a production company, AIFOS<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/disney-channel-sofia-wylie-aifos-productions-company-1202570845/|title=Disney Channel Star Sofia Wylie Launches AIFOS Productions Company|last=Amanda|first=N'Duka|journal=Deadline|date=6 March 2019|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref> and is set to adapt Jenny Torres Sanchez's novel, ''The Fall of Innocence,'' as its first project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thefandom.net/disney-star-options-rights-to-ya-drama-the-fall-of-innocence/|title=Disney Star Options Rights To YA Drama 'The Fall of Innocence''|journal=The Fandom|date=March 8, 2019|accessdate=June 9, 2019}}</ref> In June 2019, Wylie signed with [[United Talent Agency]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/uta-signs-disney-channel-star-sofia-wylie-1220232|title=UTA Signs Disney Channel Star Sofia Wylie (Exclusive)|journal=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Rebecca|last=Sun|date=June 20, 2019|accessdate=August 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! class=\"unsortable\" | {{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 2011, 2016 \n| ''[[So You Think You Can Dance (U.S. TV series)|So You Think You Can Dance]]'' \n| Herself \n| Dancer; 2 episodes \n|\n|-\n| 2015 \n| ''[[America's Got Talent]]'' \n| Herself \n| Dancer; 1 episode \n|\n|-\n| 2017 \n| ''[[Nicky, Ricky, Dicky & Dawn]]'' \n| June \n| 3 episodes\n| <ref name=\"DisneyABCPress-Andi Mack-Bios\"/>\n|-\n| 2017\u20132019\n| ''[[Andi Mack]]'' \n| Buffy Driscoll \n| Main role \n| <ref name=\"anthem news\"/>\n|-\n| 2019 \n| ''[[Marvel Rising]]: Heart of Iron'' \n| [[Ironheart (character)|Ironheart / Riri Williams]] \n| Voice role; television film \n| <ref name=\"hoi 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.marvel.com/articles/tv-shows/two-new-marvel-rising-animated-specials-are-coming-your-way|title=Two New 'Marvel Rising' Animated Specials Are Coming Your Way|first=Christine|last=Dinh|journal=Marvel|date=2 October 2018|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019 \n| ''[[Back of the Net]]'' \n| Cory Bailey \n| Film\n| <ref name=\"botn 1\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/andi-mack-star-sofia-wylie-scores-big-screen-role-with-australian-feature-back-of-the-net-1202354599/|title=\u2018Andi Mack\u2019 Star Sofia Wylie Scores Big Screen Role With Australian Soccer Feature \u2018Back Of The Net\u2019|first=Peter|last=White|journal=Deadline|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019 \n| ''[[Marvel Rising]]: Battle of the Bands'' \n| [[Ironheart (character)|Ironheart / Riri Williams]] \n| Voice role; special\n| \n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Shook (web series)|Shook]]'' \n| Amelia \"Mia\" Brooks\n| Web miniseries; main role\n| <ref name=\"shook announcement\">{{cite web|url=https://discussingfilm.net/2019/08/01/sofia-wylie-cast-in-shook-series-for-disney-exclusive/|title=Sofia Wylie Cast In \u2018Shook\u2019 Series For Disney+ (EXCLUSIVE)|first=Jacob|last=Fisher|journal=DiscussingFilm|date=1 August 2019|accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019\u2013present\n| ''[[High School Musical: The Musical: The Series]]'' \n| Gina Porter\n| Main role \n| <ref name=\"hsm announcement\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1015582/meet-the-cast-of-disney-s-high-school-musical-the-musical-the-series|title=Meet the Cast of Disney's High School Musical: The Musical: The Series|first=Chris|last=Harnick|journal=E! News|date=15 February 2019|accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Spider-Man: Maximum Venom]]''\n| Ironheart / Riri Williams\n| ''Upcoming'' (season 3)\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|8402202}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wylie, Sofia}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2004 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Scottsdale, Arizona]]\n[[Category:African-American child actresses]]\n[[Category:African-American female dancers]]\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:American actresses of Korean descent]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American female singers]]\n[[Category:American film production company founders]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:American web series actresses]]\n", "name_user": "201.174.234.218", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sofia_Wylie"}
{"title_page": "Rickwood Field", "text_new": "{{container}}\n\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name        = Rickwood Field\n| logo_image          = \n| image               = Rickwood Field.jpg\n| caption             = \n| location            = 1137 2nd Avenue West, [[Birmingham, Alabama]]\n| coordinates         = \n| broke_ground        = Spring 1910\n| cost                = $75,000\n| opened              = August 18, 1910\n| owner               = City of Birmingham\n| operator            = \n| surface             = Grass\n| architect           = \n| tenants             = \n[[Birmingham Barons]] (Southern Association) \u2013 1910&ndash;1961<br/>\n[[Birmingham Barons]] (Southern League) \u2013 1964&ndash;1965, 1981&ndash;1987, part-time 1988&ndash;present<br/>\n[[Birmingham A's]] (Southern League) \u2013 1967&ndash;1975<br/>\n[[Birmingham Black Barons]] (Negro Southern League) \u2013 1920&ndash;1924, 1926, 1931&ndash;1936, 1938&ndash;1939 <br/>\n[[Birmingham Black Barons]] (Negro National League) \u2013 1925&ndash;1926, 1927&ndash;1930, 1937, 1940&ndash;1948 <br/>\n[[Birmingham Black Barons]] (Negro American League) \u2013 1949&ndash;1960 <br/>\n[[Philadelphia Phillies]] (Major League Baseball Spring Training) - 1911, 1920 <br/>\n[[Pittsburgh Pirates]] (Major League Baseball Spring Training) - 1919 \n| seating_capacity    = 10,800\n| record_attendance   = \n| dimensions          = \nLeft field: {{convert|321|ft|m}}<br/>\nLeft center: {{convert|399|ft|m}}<br/>\nCenter field: {{convert|393|ft|m}}<br/>\nRight center: {{convert|392|ft|m}}<br/>\nRight field: {{convert|332|ft|m}}\n{{Infobox NRHP|embed=yes\n  | name = Rickwood Field\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = \n  | caption = \n  | location= \n  | coordinates = {{coord|33|30|8|N|86|51|21|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = \n  | built = 1910\n  | architecture = \n  | added = February 1, 1993\n  | area = {{convert|12.7|acre}}\n  | governing_body =\n  | refnum = 92001826<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n | designated_other1 = ARLH\n | designated_other1_date = December 19, 1991\n}}\n}}\n'''Rickwood Field''', located in [[Birmingham, Alabama]], is the oldest professional [[baseball]] park in the United States. It was built for the [[Birmingham Barons]] in 1910 by industrialist and team-owner [[Rick Woodward]] and has served as the home park for the Birmingham Barons and the [[Birmingham Black Barons]] of the [[Negro League baseball|Negro Leagues]]. Though the Barons moved their home games to the Hoover Met in the suburbs, and most recently to [[Regions Field]] in Birmingham, Rickwood Field has been preserved and is undergoing gradual restoration as a \"working museum\" where baseball's history can be experienced. The Barons also play one regular season game a year at Rickwood Field.  Rickwood Field is listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe Birmingham Coal Barons baseball team began playing professionally in 1887, with their home games at an informal park called \"Slag Pile Field\" in West End. In 1901 they joined the [[Southern Association]].\n\nAllen Harvey \"Rick\" Woodward, chairman of Woodward Iron Company and grandson of pioneer Birmingham industrialist Stimpson Harvey Woodward, purchased a majority share of the Birmingham Coal Barons baseball team from J. William McQueen in 1909 while he was still in his 20s. Immediately he began planning a grand showplace for his new team. He contacted [[Connie Mack]] for advice on the details, including the field dimensions. He settled on [[Shibe Park]] in [[Philadelphia]] (which was controlled by Mack's team and later renamed Connie Mack Stadium) and [[Forbes Field]] in [[Pittsburgh]] as the models for the new park. He purchased land in the West End neighborhood of Birmingham from the Alabama Central Railroad. The $75,000 structure was designed by Southeastern Engineering Company of Birmingham (a short-lived subsidiary of [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]]'s General Fireproofing Company) and completed during the summer of 1910. The 12.7 [[acre]] (51,000&nbsp;m\u00b2) park was flanked along the basepaths by concrete and steel stands. A tile-roofed cupola on the roof behind home plate provided space for the announcer and the press. Woodward named the field after himself, using his nickname and the first part of his last name.  It was the first concrete-and-steel stadium in the minors.\n\nWoodward invited Alabama Governor [[Braxton Bragg Comer]], Birmingham Mayor Culpepper Exum, civic leader, [[George B. Ward]] and Victor H. Hanson, publisher of ''[[The Birmingham News]]'', for opening day on August 18, 1910. The day was celebrated by businesses closing all over town to allow fans to fill the park for the first pitch at 3:30 P.M. Over 10,000 people attended that first game in which the Barons defeated the visiting Montgomery Climbers 3-2. Throughout the first half of the 20th century Rickwood Field hosted sellout crowds for both the Barons and the Black Barons, who played on alternate weekends.\n\nIn 1912 a spring [[tornado]] tore through the field, pulling up the outfield fence. Two years later Woodward felt the need to have electric fans installed in the grandstands for the comfort of the crowd. The [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] also made Rickwood Field their [[spring training]] home in [[1919 in baseball|1919]].\n\nRickwood Field also hosted [[college football]] games. From 1912 to 1927 the [[Alabama Crimson Tide]] played its Birmingham home dates in Rickwood.  In 1921 the outfield fence was damaged in a tornado and quickly rebuilt. In 1924\u20131927 the infield bleachers were covered with a steel-framed roof designed by Denham, VanKeuren & Denham, Architects of Birmingham. Shortly after, In 1928 a new [[Mission Revival Style architecture|Mission style]] entry structure with offices was built to the designs of Paul Wright & Co., Engineers of Birmingham. A new concrete outfield wall replaced the original fence.\n\nIn 1931 in the first game of the Dixie Series championship, Birmingham's 43-year-old [[Ray Caldwell]] outpitched 22-year-old [[Dizzy Dean]], who had guaranteed a win. The Barons won the series 4 games to 3. In 1936 four monumental steel-frame light towers designed and fabricated by the Truscon Steel Company of [[Youngstown, Ohio]] were erected, allowing for night games. In 1938, Woodward sold the park to Ed Norton, a local businessman. In 1940 Norton sold it to the Cincinnati Reds. At that time new outfield fences were built inside the original walls to reduce the field dimensions.  G. J. Jebeles of Birmingham purchased the park in 1944. A ladies' rest room was added and the outfield fence reduced again in 1948. In 1949 ownership changed hands again, going to a partnership of Al DeMent, Al Belcher, and Rufus Lackey. They added a small restaurant in the entrance building in 1950 and installed additional box seats, necessitating the relocations of the dugouts farther down the baselines. In 1958 Belcher gained a majority share and control of the park. In 1964 General Manager Glynn West purchased 1000 wooden seats from New York City's [[Polo Grounds]] and installed them at the park. Belcher sold Rickwood Field in 1966 to the City of Birmingham, but retained a lease for the remainder of that year.\n\nIn 1966 the lease was transferred to [[Charles O. Finley|Charlie Finley]], who brought the [[Oakland Athletics|Kansas City Athletics']] AA farm team to Birmingham for the 1967 season. That year is remembered for the day that 14,000 disappointed fans were sent home early when the [[Atlanta Braves]] vs. Southern League All-Stars exhibition game was called \"on account of tornado.\"  During this period, following a trend which swept [[minor league baseball]] (and which has since been largely reversed), the team took the name of the parent [[Major League Baseball|major league]] club and was known as the \"Birmingham A's\". Between 1979 and 1980 the wooden seats were replaced with plastic seats in the box areas and metal bleachers under the grandstands.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mercer|first=Chloe S.|author2=Melanie A. Betz|title=Rickwood Field |url={{NRHP url|id=92001826}}|work=National Register of Historic Places Registration Form|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=March 17, 2014|date=August 19, 1992|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6O9gfxXrB |archivedate=March 17, 2014|url-status=live}} ''See also:'' {{cite web|title=Accompanying photos|url={{NRHP url|id=92001826|photos=y}}|accessdate=March 17, 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6O9ggh0zK |archivedate=March 17, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981 Art Clarkson brought minor league baseball back to Rickwood with the Detroit Tigers AA club, which resumed the Barons name. He had a new electronic scoreboard installed at the park. In 1986, the Barons became the Chicago White Sox AA club, an affiliation that continues today.\n\nIn 1987 the Barons moved to a new facility, [[Hoover Metropolitan Stadium]], in the [[suburb]] of [[Hoover, Alabama|Hoover]].  They returned to Birmingham in 2013 with the opening of [[Regions Field]], just south of downtown Birmingham.\n\n==Current status==\nSince 1992 the ballpark has been under the care of the [http://www.rickwood.com Friends of Rickwood] who are restoring the facility to its former glory. They also host frequent amateur, police and semi-pro games and open the gates to visitors who can walk in and explore the grandstands or run the bases.\n\nSince 1996, Rickwood Field has hosted the Barons for a throwback game in which both teams wear period uniforms. Each game honors a different era in Birmingham baseball history. Ballpark enthusiasts from across North America migrate to Rickwood to attend this AA regulation game, named the \"Rickwood Classic\", every season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cullmantimes.com/news/column-rickwood-field-nation-s-oldest-ballpark-still-making-memories/article_1e246aa8-830a-11e9-9c8b-8ba4f21ab638.html|title=Rickwood Field, nation's oldest ballpark, still making memories|last=Newberry|first=Paul|date=May 31, 2019|website=The Cullman Times|language=en|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref> Many consider this game the best opportunity to experience a regulation ballgame in an historic ballpark that remains true to its original and traditional appearance. Those involved \u2013 the Barons franchise, Friends of Rickwood, and fans \u2013 fully believe that this experience in the sacred baseball cathedral is among the most underrated baseball events.\n\nScenes from the movies ''[[Cobb (film)|Cobb]]'' (1994) and ''Soul of the Game'' (1995) were filmed at Rickwood. Those productions contributed to the recreation of the scoreboard and press-box and the addition of 1940s period style advertisements on the outfield fence. Some of these retro-style ads have been sponsored by real Birmingham businesses, including a section sponsored by the descendants of Rick Woodward that advertises long-gone Woodward Iron Co. The outfield signs were designed by Ted Haigh, a Los Angeles-based graphic designer and executed by Skidmore Sign Company of Birmingham.\nIn May 2012, scenes from the [[film|movie]] ''[[42 (film)|42]]'' were also filmed at Rickwood Field.\n\nAs of 2005, the Friends of Rickwood have spent around $2&nbsp;million refurbishing the grandstands, press-box, locker rooms, roof and main entrance to the park. Future plans include establishing a Museum of Southern Baseball.\n\nSince 2011 Play at the Plate Baseball has held an annual 3 day adult baseball tournament with 4 teams from various regions of the country participating. The event is usually held in June.\n\n[[ESPN Classic]] broadcast a re-enactment of a [[Negro Leagues|Negro League]] game played at Rickwood on February 26, 2006. It featured teams wearing the uniforms of the fictitious \"Bristol Barnstormers\" (named for ESPN's hometown of [[Bristol, Connecticut]]) and the [[Birmingham Black Barons]].\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Rickwood entrance.png|Rickwood Field facade\nImage:Rickwood site plan.png|Plan of the field\nImage:Post-game fun.jpg|Field\nImage:Birmingham Black Baron's Left Fielder.jpg|Scoreboard\nImage:Rickwood Championships.jpg|Rickwood Championships\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Warren Ballpark]] in [[Bisbee, Arizona]]. Its grounds hosted professional baseball in 1909, but the present stadium dates to the 1930s.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{cite book | author=Benson, Michael | title=Ballparks of North America: A Comprehensive Historical Reference to Grounds, Yards, and Stadiums, 1845-Present | publisher=McFarlands | year=1989 | id=ISBN}}\n*Wainwright, Paige. \"Rickwood Field: Grand Old Lady of Baseball.\" ''Alabama Heritage'', Fall 1995.\n*{{cite book | author=Whitt, Timothy | title=Bases Loaded with History: The Story of Rickwood Field: America's Oldest Baseball Park | location=Birmingham, Alabama | publisher=R. Boozer Press | year=1995 | isbn=0-9636128-1-6}}\n*[[United States Geological Survey]] (2006). {{Gnis3|125622}}. Retrieved 1 February 2006.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Rickwood Field}}\n* [http://www.rickwood.com Rickwood Field (Friends of Rickwood) website]\n* [http://www.baseballpilgrimages.com/rickwood.html Rickwood Field at Baseball Pilgrimages.com]\n* {{HABS |survey=AL-897 |id=al0965 |title=Rickwood Field, 1137 Second Avenue West, Birmingham, Jefferson County, AL |photos=28 |color= |dwgs=22 |data=58 |cap=2}}\n* [https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/pauls2004parks/Stadiums/Birmingham/Rickwood.htm&date=2009-10-26+00:19:21 Rickwood Field Views - ''Ball Parks of the Minor Leagues'']\n\n{{Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{Samford Bulldogs football navbox}}\n{{Philadelphia Phillies}}\n{{Pittsburgh Pirates}}\n{{Birmingham Landmarks}}\n\n[[Category:Baseball museums and halls of fame]]\n[[Category:Defunct college football venues]]\n[[Category:Minor league baseball venues]]\n[[Category:Negro league baseball venues]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football venues]]\n[[Category:Samford Bulldogs football]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Pirates spring training venues]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies spring training venues]]\n[[Category:International Sports Heritage Association]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Properties on the Alabama Register of Landmarks and Heritage]]\n[[Category:Museums in Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Negro league baseball venues still standing]]\n[[Category:Baseball venues in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Sports museums in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Historic American Buildings Survey in Alabama]]\n[[Category:1910 establishments in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1910]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox stadium\n| stadium_name        = Rickwood Field\n| logo_image          = \n| image               = Rickwood Field.jpg\n| caption             = \n| location            = 1137 2nd Avenue West, [[Birmingham, Alabama]]\n| coordinates         = \n| broke_ground        = Spring 1910\n| cost                = $75,000\n| opened              = August 18, 1910\n| owner               = City of Birmingham\n| operator            = \n| surface             = Grass\n| architect           = \n| tenants             = \n[[Birmingham Barons]] (Southern Association) \u2013 1910&ndash;1961<br/>\n[[Birmingham Barons]] (Southern League) \u2013 1964&ndash;1965, 1981&ndash;1987, part-time 1988&ndash;present<br/>\n[[Birmingham A's]] (Southern League) \u2013 1967&ndash;1975<br/>\n[[Birmingham Black Barons]] (Negro Southern League) \u2013 1920&ndash;1924, 1926, 1931&ndash;1936, 1938&ndash;1939 <br/>\n[[Birmingham Black Barons]] (Negro National League) \u2013 1925&ndash;1926, 1927&ndash;1930, 1937, 1940&ndash;1948 <br/>\n[[Birmingham Black Barons]] (Negro American League) \u2013 1949&ndash;1960 <br/>\n[[Philadelphia Phillies]] (Major League Baseball Spring Training) - 1911, 1920 <br/>\n[[Pittsburgh Pirates]] (Major League Baseball Spring Training) - 1919 \n| seating_capacity    = 10,800\n| record_attendance   = \n| dimensions          = \nLeft field: {{convert|321|ft|m}}<br/>\nLeft center: {{convert|399|ft|m}}<br/>\nCenter field: {{convert|393|ft|m}}<br/>\nRight center: {{convert|392|ft|m}}<br/>\nRight field: {{convert|332|ft|m}}\n{{Infobox NRHP|embed=yes\n  | name = Rickwood Field\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = \n  | caption = \n  | location= \n  | coordinates = {{coord|33|30|8|N|86|51|21|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = \n  | built = 1910\n  | architecture = \n  | added = February 1, 1993\n  | area = {{convert|12.7|acre}}\n  | governing_body =\n  | refnum = 92001826<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n | designated_other1 = ARLH\n | designated_other1_date = December 19, 1991\n}}\n}}\n'''Rickwood Field''', located in [[Birmingham, Alabama]], is the oldest professional [[baseball]] park in the United States. It was built for the [[Birmingham Barons]] in 1910 by industrialist and team-owner [[Rick Woodward]] and has served as the home park for the Birmingham Barons and the [[Birmingham Black Barons]] of the [[Negro League baseball|Negro Leagues]]. Though the Barons moved their home games to the Hoover Met in the suburbs, and most recently to [[Regions Field]] in Birmingham, Rickwood Field has been preserved and is undergoing gradual restoration as a \"working museum\" where baseball's history can be experienced. The Barons also play one regular season game a year at Rickwood Field.  Rickwood Field is listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe Birmingham Coal Barons baseball team began playing professionally in 1887, with their home games at an informal park called \"Slag Pile Field\" in West End. In 1901 they joined the [[Southern Association]].\n\nAllen Harvey \"Rick\" Woodward, chairman of Woodward Iron Company and grandson of pioneer Birmingham industrialist Stimpson Harvey Woodward, purchased a majority share of the Birmingham Coal Barons baseball team from J. William McQueen in 1909 while he was still in his 20s. Immediately he began planning a grand showplace for his new team. He contacted [[Connie Mack]] for advice on the details, including the field dimensions. He settled on [[Shibe Park]] in [[Philadelphia]] (which was controlled by Mack's team and later renamed Connie Mack Stadium) and [[Forbes Field]] in [[Pittsburgh]] as the models for the new park. He purchased land in the West End neighborhood of Birmingham from the Alabama Central Railroad. The $75,000 structure was designed by Southeastern Engineering Company of Birmingham (a short-lived subsidiary of [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]]'s General Fireproofing Company) and completed during the summer of 1910. The 12.7 [[acre]] (51,000&nbsp;m\u00b2) park was flanked along the basepaths by concrete and steel stands. A tile-roofed cupola on the roof behind home plate provided space for the announcer and the press. Woodward named the field after himself, using his nickname and the first part of his last name.  It was the first concrete-and-steel stadium in the minors.\n\nWoodward invited Alabama Governor [[Braxton Bragg Comer]], Birmingham Mayor Culpepper Exum, civic leader, [[George B. Ward]] and Victor H. Hanson, publisher of ''[[The Birmingham News]]'', for opening day on August 18, 1910. The day was celebrated by businesses closing all over town to allow fans to fill the park for the first pitch at 3:30 P.M. Over 10,000 people attended that first game in which the Barons defeated the visiting Montgomery Climbers 3-2. Throughout the first half of the 20th century Rickwood Field hosted sellout crowds for both the Barons and the Black Barons, who played on alternate weekends.\n\nIn 1912 a spring [[tornado]] tore through the field, pulling up the outfield fence. Two years later Woodward felt the need to have electric fans installed in the grandstands for the comfort of the crowd. The [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] also made Rickwood Field their [[spring training]] home in [[1919 in baseball|1919]].\n\nRickwood Field also hosted [[college football]] games. From 1912 to 1927 the [[Alabama Crimson Tide]] played its Birmingham home dates in Rickwood.  In 1921 the outfield fence was damaged in a tornado and quickly rebuilt. In 1924\u20131927 the infield bleachers were covered with a steel-framed roof designed by Denham, VanKeuren & Denham, Architects of Birmingham. Shortly after, In 1928 a new [[Mission Revival Style architecture|Mission style]] entry structure with offices was built to the designs of Paul Wright & Co., Engineers of Birmingham. A new concrete outfield wall replaced the original fence.\n\nIn 1931 in the first game of the Dixie Series championship, Birmingham's 43-year-old [[Ray Caldwell]] outpitched 22-year-old [[Dizzy Dean]], who had guaranteed a win. The Barons won the series 4 games to 3. In 1936 four monumental steel-frame light towers designed and fabricated by the Truscon Steel Company of [[Youngstown, Ohio]] were erected, allowing for night games. In 1938, Woodward sold the park to Ed Norton, a local businessman. In 1940 Norton sold it to the Cincinnati Reds. At that time new outfield fences were built inside the original walls to reduce the field dimensions.  G. J. Jebeles of Birmingham purchased the park in 1944. A ladies' rest room was added and the outfield fence reduced again in 1948. In 1949 ownership changed hands again, going to a partnership of Al DeMent, Al Belcher, and Rufus Lackey. They added a small restaurant in the entrance building in 1950 and installed additional box seats, necessitating the relocations of the dugouts farther down the baselines. In 1958 Belcher gained a majority share and control of the park. In 1964 General Manager Glynn West purchased 1000 wooden seats from New York City's [[Polo Grounds]] and installed them at the park. Belcher sold Rickwood Field in 1966 to the City of Birmingham, but retained a lease for the remainder of that year.\n\nIn 1966 the lease was transferred to [[Charles O. Finley|Charlie Finley]], who brought the [[Oakland Athletics|Kansas City Athletics']] AA farm team to Birmingham for the 1967 season. That year is remembered for the day that 14,000 disappointed fans were sent home early when the [[Atlanta Braves]] vs. Southern League All-Stars exhibition game was called \"on account of tornado.\"  During this period, following a trend which swept [[minor league baseball]] (and which has since been largely reversed), the team took the name of the parent [[Major League Baseball|major league]] club and was known as the \"Birmingham A's\". Between 1979 and 1980 the wooden seats were replaced with plastic seats in the box areas and metal bleachers under the grandstands.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mercer|first=Chloe S.|author2=Melanie A. Betz|title=Rickwood Field |url={{NRHP url|id=92001826}}|work=National Register of Historic Places Registration Form|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=March 17, 2014|date=August 19, 1992|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6O9gfxXrB |archivedate=March 17, 2014|url-status=live}} ''See also:'' {{cite web|title=Accompanying photos|url={{NRHP url|id=92001826|photos=y}}|accessdate=March 17, 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6O9ggh0zK |archivedate=March 17, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981 Art Clarkson brought minor league baseball back to Rickwood with the Detroit Tigers AA club, which resumed the Barons name. He had a new electronic scoreboard installed at the park. In 1986, the Barons became the Chicago White Sox AA club, an affiliation that continues today.\n\nIn 1987 the Barons moved to a new facility, [[Hoover Metropolitan Stadium]], in the [[suburb]] of [[Hoover, Alabama|Hoover]].  They returned to Birmingham in 2013 with the opening of [[Regions Field]], just south of downtown Birmingham.\n\n==Current status==\nSince 1992 the ballpark has been under the care of the [http://www.rickwood.com Friends of Rickwood] who are restoring the facility to its former glory. They also host frequent amateur, police and semi-pro games and open the gates to visitors who can walk in and explore the grandstands or run the bases.\n\nSince 1996, Rickwood Field has hosted the Barons for a throwback game in which both teams wear period uniforms. Each game honors a different era in Birmingham baseball history. Ballpark enthusiasts from across North America migrate to Rickwood to attend this AA regulation game, named the \"Rickwood Classic\", every season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cullmantimes.com/news/column-rickwood-field-nation-s-oldest-ballpark-still-making-memories/article_1e246aa8-830a-11e9-9c8b-8ba4f21ab638.html|title=Rickwood Field, nation's oldest ballpark, still making memories|last=Newberry|first=Paul|date=May 31, 2019|website=The Cullman Times|language=en|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref> Many consider this game the best opportunity to experience a regulation ballgame in an historic ballpark that remains true to its original and traditional appearance. Those involved \u2013 the Barons franchise, Friends of Rickwood, and fans \u2013 fully believe that this experience in the sacred baseball cathedral is among the most underrated baseball events.\n\nScenes from the movies ''[[Cobb (film)|Cobb]]'' (1994) and ''Soul of the Game'' (1995) were filmed at Rickwood. Those productions contributed to the recreation of the scoreboard and press-box and the addition of 1940s period style advertisements on the outfield fence. Some of these retro-style ads have been sponsored by real Birmingham businesses, including a section sponsored by the descendants of Rick Woodward that advertises long-gone Woodward Iron Co. The outfield signs were designed by Ted Haigh, a Los Angeles-based graphic designer and executed by Skidmore Sign Company of Birmingham.\nIn May 2012, scenes from the [[film|movie]] ''[[42 (film)|42]]'' were also filmed at Rickwood Field.\n\nAs of 2005, the Friends of Rickwood have spent around $2&nbsp;million refurbishing the grandstands, press-box, locker rooms, roof and main entrance to the park. Future plans include establishing a Museum of Southern Baseball.\n\nSince 2011 Play at the Plate Baseball has held an annual 3 day adult baseball tournament with 4 teams from various regions of the country participating. The event is usually held in June.\n\n[[ESPN Classic]] broadcast a re-enactment of a [[Negro Leagues|Negro League]] game played at Rickwood on February 26, 2006. It featured teams wearing the uniforms of the fictitious \"Bristol Barnstormers\" (named for ESPN's hometown of [[Bristol, Connecticut]]) and the [[Birmingham Black Barons]].\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Rickwood entrance.png|Rickwood Field facade\nImage:Rickwood site plan.png|Plan of the field\nImage:Post-game fun.jpg|Field\nImage:Birmingham Black Baron's Left Fielder.jpg|Scoreboard\nImage:Rickwood Championships.jpg|Rickwood Championships\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Warren Ballpark]] in [[Bisbee, Arizona]]. Its grounds hosted professional baseball in 1909, but the present stadium dates to the 1930s.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{cite book | author=Benson, Michael | title=Ballparks of North America: A Comprehensive Historical Reference to Grounds, Yards, and Stadiums, 1845-Present | publisher=McFarlands | year=1989 | id=ISBN}}\n*Wainwright, Paige. \"Rickwood Field: Grand Old Lady of Baseball.\" ''Alabama Heritage'', Fall 1995.\n*{{cite book | author=Whitt, Timothy | title=Bases Loaded with History: The Story of Rickwood Field: America's Oldest Baseball Park | location=Birmingham, Alabama | publisher=R. Boozer Press | year=1995 | isbn=0-9636128-1-6}}\n*[[United States Geological Survey]] (2006). {{Gnis3|125622}}. Retrieved 1 February 2006.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Rickwood Field}}\n* [http://www.rickwood.com Rickwood Field (Friends of Rickwood) website]\n* [http://www.baseballpilgrimages.com/rickwood.html Rickwood Field at Baseball Pilgrimages.com]\n* {{HABS |survey=AL-897 |id=al0965 |title=Rickwood Field, 1137 Second Avenue West, Birmingham, Jefferson County, AL |photos=28 |color= |dwgs=22 |data=58 |cap=2}}\n* [https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/pauls2004parks/Stadiums/Birmingham/Rickwood.htm&date=2009-10-26+00:19:21 Rickwood Field Views - ''Ball Parks of the Minor Leagues'']\n\n{{Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{Samford Bulldogs football navbox}}\n{{Philadelphia Phillies}}\n{{Pittsburgh Pirates}}\n{{Birmingham Landmarks}}\n\n[[Category:Baseball museums and halls of fame]]\n[[Category:Defunct college football venues]]\n[[Category:Minor league baseball venues]]\n[[Category:Negro league baseball venues]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football venues]]\n[[Category:Samford Bulldogs football]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Pirates spring training venues]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies spring training venues]]\n[[Category:International Sports Heritage Association]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Properties on the Alabama Register of Landmarks and Heritage]]\n[[Category:Museums in Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Negro league baseball venues still standing]]\n[[Category:Baseball venues in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Sports museums in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Historic American Buildings Survey in Alabama]]\n[[Category:1910 establishments in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1910]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rickwood_Field"}
{"title_page": "Old State Bank (Decatur, Alabama)", "text_new": "{{container}}\n\n{{more citations needed|date=May 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name =State Bank Building, Decatur Branch\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Old State Bank Decatur July 2010 02.jpg\n  | caption = \n  | location= 925 Bank St., NE, [[Decatur, Alabama]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|34|36|52|N|86|59|1|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin =\n  | area =\n  | built =1833\n  | architect= Jefferson Steelflex\n  | architecture= [[Jeffersonian architecture|Jeffersonian]]\n  | added = March 24, 1972\n  | governing_body = Private\n  | refnum=72000176<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''State Bank Building, Decatur Branch''', commonly known as the '''Old State Bank''', is a historic [[Jeffersonian architecture|Jeffersonian]]-style bank building in [[Decatur, Alabama]], [[United States]]. It was recorded by the [[Historic American Buildings Survey]] in 1934 and 1935.  It was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on March 24, 1972, due to its architectural significance.<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe Decatur branch of the Alabama State Bank opened its doors on July 29, 1833. It was authorized by the [[Alabama General Assembly]] in 1830 to be one of three branches of the Alabama State Bank. After outstanding debts of over $1 million were unable to be reformed the Decatur branch franchise was revoked. The building remained vacant until the 1860s when it was one of four buildings that survived the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] in [[Decatur, Alabama]].  During the [[Battle of Decatur]], the bank was used as headquarters for the [[Union Army|Union forces]] in the area and was also used as a hospital while battles raged outside.  Such evidence of the battle remains: bloodstains are visible in one of the three vaults and slugs from musket fire and [[Mini\u00e9 ball]]s are still clearly seen in the walls of the building.\n\nIn 1881, the [[First National Bank of Decatur|First National Bank]] opened its doors in the Old State Bank building.  But, when First National Bank completed its new office in 1902, the bank building was used as a residence and office by J. Y. Cantwell.  After signs of deterioration began to show themselves, Cantwell's grand niece, W. B. Edmundson, deeded the building over to the City of Decatur in 1933.  Management of the structure was vested in an eight-member Board of Governors.  The petition for restoration was presented to the Civil Works Administration and restoration commenced.  Being one of only a handful of local buildings to survive the destruction of the [[American Civil War]], and after going through the many changes over the years, the Old State Bank has become a symbol of historical significance.\n\nBy the year 1946, the building was deeded by its owner to the Morgan County [[American Legion]], Post No. 15.  At some point, the original bank building was completely obscured by a brick facade which also enclosed the front portico and columns.  The appearance was simply a huge, ugly, brick warehouse and, by the early 1970s, the original history was long forgotten.  As part of a plan to remove aging, blighted buildings, a demolition crew was contracted to tear down the old building with a wrecking ball.  It was soon obvious that something unusual was present when the wrecking ball could tear right through the front wall at some places, but the heavy ball bounced off other spots.  The invincible spots were found to be the five limestone columns hidden behind bricks for generations.  (A few of the columns still carry wrecking ball scars.)  The project to demolish the old, blighted warehouse quickly transformed into restoring this centerpiece of a newly formed historical district.\n\n[[File:Alabama winter 2008.jpg|thumb|left|The fountains in front of the Old State Bank frozen in winter 2008.]]\n\nIn 1972, the Old State Bank was named to the National Register of Historical Places at the age of 139 years.  Three years later, in 1975, the American Legion, Post No. 15, donated the Old State Bank building to the City of Decatur.  Plans for restoration were put together in the year 1976, as the bank turned 143 years old, and was put under the control of the Old Bank Board members.  Restoration of the bank was finished in the year 1983, at the age of 150. In 1984, a curator was appointed, and daily tours were implemented.  The second wave of detailed restoration was undertaken in the years of 1995-1996 and was led by noted preservation architect, Harvie Jones.  Funding was provided by the Alabama Historical Commission, the City of Decatur, and the Old Bank Board of Directors.  The City of Decatur commemorated the bank's 175th anniversary in 2008.\n\n== Architecture ==\nThe architecture of the bank shows the influence of [[Thomas Jefferson]]'s fusion of [[Palladian architecture|Palladianism]] with [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] temple forms. The five limestone columns across the front weigh 100-150 tons each and were mined in nearby [[Trinity, Alabama|Trinity]]. The pentastyle portico is highly unusual.<ref name=\"gamble\">{{cite book |title=Historic architecture in Alabama: a guide to styles and types, 1810-1930 |last=Gamble |first=Robert |year=1990 |publisher=University of Alabama Press |location=Tuscaloosa, Alabama |isbn=0-8173-1134-3 |page=53 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Morgan County, Alabama]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.decaturparks.com/account.php?accountid=45 Old State Bank] - Decatur Parks and Recreation Department\n*{{Commons category-inline|Old State Bank}}\n*{{HABS |survey=AL-348 |id=al0668 |title=State Bank of Alabama, Decatur Branch, Bank Street & Wilson Avenue, Decatur, Morgan County, AL |photos=6 |dwgs=9 |data=4 |cap=1 |supp=yes}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Decatur, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Parks in Decatur, Alabama]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Morgan County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Historic American Buildings Survey in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Palladian Revival architecture in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Alabama in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Historic bank buildings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Commercial buildings completed in 1833]]\n[[Category:Bank buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Alabama]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=May 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name =State Bank Building, Decatur Branch\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Old State Bank Decatur July 2010 02.jpg\n  | caption = \n  | location= 925 Bank St., NE, [[Decatur, Alabama]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|34|36|52|N|86|59|1|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin =\n  | area =\n  | built =1833\n  | architect= Jefferson Steelflex\n  | architecture= [[Jeffersonian architecture|Jeffersonian]]\n  | added = March 24, 1972\n  | governing_body = Private\n  | refnum=72000176<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''State Bank Building, Decatur Branch''', commonly known as the '''Old State Bank''', is a historic [[Jeffersonian architecture|Jeffersonian]]-style bank building in [[Decatur, Alabama]], [[United States]]. It was recorded by the [[Historic American Buildings Survey]] in 1934 and 1935.  It was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on March 24, 1972, due to its architectural significance.<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe Decatur branch of the Alabama State Bank opened its doors on July 29, 1833. It was authorized by the [[Alabama General Assembly]] in 1830 to be one of three branches of the Alabama State Bank. After outstanding debts of over $1 million were unable to be reformed the Decatur branch franchise was revoked. The building remained vacant until the 1860s when it was one of four buildings that survived the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] in [[Decatur, Alabama]].  During the [[Battle of Decatur]], the bank was used as headquarters for the [[Union Army|Union forces]] in the area and was also used as a hospital while battles raged outside.  Such evidence of the battle remains: bloodstains are visible in one of the three vaults and slugs from musket fire and [[Mini\u00e9 ball]]s are still clearly seen in the walls of the building.\n\nIn 1881, the [[First National Bank of Decatur|First National Bank]] opened its doors in the Old State Bank building.  But, when First National Bank completed its new office in 1902, the bank building was used as a residence and office by J. Y. Cantwell.  After signs of deterioration began to show themselves, Cantwell's grand niece, W. B. Edmundson, deeded the building over to the City of Decatur in 1933.  Management of the structure was vested in an eight-member Board of Governors.  The petition for restoration was presented to the Civil Works Administration and restoration commenced.  Being one of only a handful of local buildings to survive the destruction of the [[American Civil War]], and after going through the many changes over the years, the Old State Bank has become a symbol of historical significance.\n\nBy the year 1946, the building was deeded by its owner to the Morgan County [[American Legion]], Post No. 15.  At some point, the original bank building was completely obscured by a brick facade which also enclosed the front portico and columns.  The appearance was simply a huge, ugly, brick warehouse and, by the early 1970s, the original history was long forgotten.  As part of a plan to remove aging, blighted buildings, a demolition crew was contracted to tear down the old building with a wrecking ball.  It was soon obvious that something unusual was present when the wrecking ball could tear right through the front wall at some places, but the heavy ball bounced off other spots.  The invincible spots were found to be the five limestone columns hidden behind bricks for generations.  (A few of the columns still carry wrecking ball scars.)  The project to demolish the old, blighted warehouse quickly transformed into restoring this centerpiece of a newly formed historical district.\n\n[[File:Alabama winter 2008.jpg|thumb|left|The fountains in front of the Old State Bank frozen in winter 2008.]]\n\nIn 1972, the Old State Bank was named to the National Register of Historical Places at the age of 139 years.  Three years later, in 1975, the American Legion, Post No. 15, donated the Old State Bank building to the City of Decatur.  Plans for restoration were put together in the year 1976, as the bank turned 143 years old, and was put under the control of the Old Bank Board members.  Restoration of the bank was finished in the year 1983, at the age of 150. In 1984, a curator was appointed, and daily tours were implemented.  The second wave of detailed restoration was undertaken in the years of 1995-1996 and was led by noted preservation architect, Harvie Jones.  Funding was provided by the Alabama Historical Commission, the City of Decatur, and the Old Bank Board of Directors.  The City of Decatur commemorated the bank's 175th anniversary in 2008.\n\n== Architecture ==\nThe architecture of the bank shows the influence of [[Thomas Jefferson]]'s fusion of [[Palladian architecture|Palladianism]] with [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] temple forms. The five limestone columns across the front weigh 100-150 tons each and were mined in nearby [[Trinity, Alabama|Trinity]]. The pentastyle portico is highly unusual.<ref name=\"gamble\">{{cite book |title=Historic architecture in Alabama: a guide to styles and types, 1810-1930 |last=Gamble |first=Robert |year=1990 |publisher=University of Alabama Press |location=Tuscaloosa, Alabama |isbn=0-8173-1134-3 |page=53 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Morgan County, Alabama]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.decaturparks.com/account.php?accountid=45 Old State Bank] - Decatur Parks and Recreation Department\n*{{Commonscat-inline|Old State Bank}}\n*{{HABS |survey=AL-348 |id=al0668 |title=State Bank of Alabama, Decatur Branch, Bank Street & Wilson Avenue, Decatur, Morgan County, AL |photos=6 |dwgs=9 |data=4 |cap=1 |supp=yes}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Decatur, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Parks in Decatur, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Alabama]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Morgan County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Historic American Buildings Survey in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Palladian Revival architecture in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Alabama in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Historic bank buildings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Commercial buildings completed in 1833]]\n[[Category:Bank buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Alabama]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_State_Bank_(Decatur,_Alabama)"}
{"title_page": "Dino (The Flintstones)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Dino (''The Flintstones'')}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color              = purple\n| name               = Dino\n| series             = [[The Flintstones]]\n| image              = Dino_from_\"The_Flintstones\".gif\n| image_size         = 150px\n| first              = The Flintstones (1960)\n| creator            = [[Hanna-Barbera]]\n| voice              = [[Mel Blanc]] (1960\u20131987, 1994, 2000)<br>Jerry Mann (1961)<br>[[Frank Welker]] (1981\u20132001)<br>[[Bill Farmer]] (2000)<br>[[Mark Mangini]] (2001)<br>[[Eric Bauza]] (2015\u2013present)\n| species            = ''Snorkasaurus''\n| spouse             = Juliet\n| gender             = Male\n| children           = 15\n}}\n'''Dino''' ({{IPAc-en|pron|\u02c8|d|i\u02d0|n|o\u028a}}) is a [[character (arts)|fictional character]] featured in the [[Hanna-Barbera]] animated [[television series]] ''[[The Flintstones]]'', and its [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]]s and [[feature film]]s. He is a pet dinosaur of the series' main characters, [[Fred Flintstone|Fred]] and [[Wilma Flintstone]].<ref>{{cite news|title= The Flintstones' 50th anniversary: 15 things you don't know|work= Daily Telegraph |date=2010-09-30|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/8034627/The-Flintstones-50th-anniversary-15-things-you-dont-know.html|accessdate=2010-10-01|location=London|first=Heidi|last=Blake}}</ref> Dino debuted in the opening credits of the pilot episode of ''The Flintstones'', but is not mentioned by name until the first season's fourth episode, \"No Help Wanted.\"\n\n==Background==\nIn the series, Dino serves the role of a pet dog, and exhibits the characteristics of a typical domesticated canine.\n\nDino is a [[prosauropod]]-like [[dinosaur]], a Snorkasaurus. Dino is a relatively small dinosaur, only slightly larger than the humans of his time, smaller than [[mammoth]]s that appear in the series, and much smaller than the numerous sauropods that appear as work animals in the series (a full-sized sauropod appears as a crane in the opening sequence, and oversized \"[[Brontosaurus|bronto]] ribs\" the size of an automobile are seen in the closing credits).\n\nA recurring gag in the series is Fred coming home from work, and Dino gets excited and knocks him down and licks his face. But no matter how hard he tries to the contrary, Fred usually gives in to Dino's ticklish and wet doglike kisses. Dino frequently exhibits human emotions, nearly \"talking,\" and can also be moved to anger, at which point he snarls and snaps, especially when Fred tries to lie either to or in front of him, which he can always tell. He also loves to play with [[Pebbles Flintstone|Pebbles]] and [[Bamm-Bamm Rubble|Bamm-Bamm]], the Flintstones' and Rubbles' respective offspring; these characters are introduced in the middle part of the series. In the episode \"Hop Happy\" Dino meets Hoppy, the Rubbles' new pet hopperoo. At first, Dino and Fred get scared, thinking he's a giant mouse, but they eventually become best friends after Hoppy helps Dino rescue their owners in an accident.\n\nAlthough he is usually immune, Dino does take a couple of brief stabs at romance.  The first comes in the episode, \"Dino Goes Hollyrock\", which originally aired on September 14, 1962.  In it, Dino falls in love with female TV star sauropod \"Sassie\" (an obvious takeoff on \"[[Lassie (1954 TV series)|Lassie]]\") and then becomes her co-star on her TV show.  However, after she removes her false eyelashes and wig, he is shocked that she turned out to be an ugly, talented sauropod that could be beautified.  The second comes in the episode, \"Dino and Juliet\", which originally aired on November 26, 1964.  In it, Dino falls in love with the new neighbor's female sauropod (Juliet).  Their romance, which results in the birth of 15 puppies, helps end the feud between Fred and the new neighbor, Mr. Loudrock.\n\nAlthough Dino had already appeared earlier in the series' first season (such as the episode \"No Help Wanted\" and \"Arthur Quarry's Dance Class\" - these episodes were made after the \"Snorkasaurus Hunter\" but aired before), Dino is portrayed quite differently in the first season's 18th episode \"The Snorkasaurus Hunter.\" In this episode, Fred and his friend [[Barney Rubble]] are on a camping trip, trying to hunt a snorkasaurus. Unlike Dino's other appearances, the snorkasaurus in this episode speaks and behaves toward Fred and Barney in a manner similar to comedian [[Phil Silvers]]. At the end of the episode, the Flintstones take in the dinosaur; the snorkasaurus (called \"Dino\" at one point by Wilma) is seen acting like a butler for the Flintstones: answering the telephone, dusting, and ironing. Dino in this episode also has purple skin instead of his varying pink-to-red color, which seems to vary from episode-to-episode during this early period, but is permanently purple after this episode. After this episode, Dino is permanently portrayed as behaving in a doglike fashion.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0580278/</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topthat.net/webrock/faq/faq10.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513034318/http://www.topthat.net/webrock/faq/faq10.htm |archivedate=2012-05-13 }}</ref>\n\nDino's origins are explained in the episode \"Dino Disappears\", which originally aired on October 10, 1963.  In it, Wilma states that Dino followed Fred home because Fred was playing with him.  Fred counters by saying he was merely trying to chase him away. This seems to refer to the episode \"Snorkasaurus Hunter\" where Fred and Barney's playing was actually hunting him down and Dino's following him was actually Dino sneaking onto the car.\n\nPost-original series, Dino appears in most of the series' spinoffs, except during the first season of ''[[The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show]]''. There, Dino is replaced by Wooly, a dwarf mammoth, as the Flintstone family's pet. However, starting with the following series' ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Hour]]'', Dino once again becomes a regular character.\n\nIn the 1980-1982 series ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Show (1980 TV series)|The Flintstone Comedy Show]]'', Dino is featured in his own segment, \"[[The Flintstone Comedy Show (1980 TV series)#Dino and Cavemouse|Dino and Cavemouse]],\" where Dino tries futilely to capture a pesky [[mouse]] in the Flintstone household. The segments bear some similarities to classic cat-and-mouse cartoons such as ''[[Tom and Jerry]]''. Dino later appears as a puppy in 1986-1988 series ''[[The Flintstone Kids]]'' (including his own segment, \"Dino's Dilemmas\"), as Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm's babysitter in the short-lived 1996 series ''[[Cave Kids]]'', and also starred in his own two 7-minute short cartoons, ''[[Dino: Stay Out!]]'' (1995) and ''[[Dino: The Great Egg-Scape]]'' (1997).\n\n==Other media==\n[[File:Dino Harikalar Diyari Flintstones 06029 nevit.jpg|thumbnail|right|Dino statue (right), along with [[Fred Flintstone]] (left).]]\nDino appears in both live-action movies. He isn't seen very often in the first film, 1994's ''[[The Flintstones (film)|The Flintstones]]''. Dino was created with both computer-generated imagery and as a puppet from [[Jim Henson's Creature Shop]], while archival audio from the original series was used to serve as Dino's voice.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nHowever, in the second film, 2000's ''[[The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas]]'', Dino has more screen time; he appears here as a puppy. Fred won Dino's egg as a prize after winning a carnival game. Initially, Fred didn't think much of the egg as he felt that the creatures inside never live long. On a [[Ferris wheel]], just as Fred and Wilma are about to kiss, Dino's egg hatches and he takes an immediate attachment to Fred, believing him to be his mother. (This, of course, contradicts Dino's origin in the original series.)\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television shows===\n* ''[[The Flintstones]]'' (1960\u20131966)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Hour]]'' (1972\u20131974)\n* ''[[Fred Flintstone and Friends]]'' (1977\u20131978)\n* ''[[The New Fred and Barney Show]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Thing]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo]]'' (1979\u20131980)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Show]]'' (1980\u20131982)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Funnies]]'' (1982\u20131984)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Kids]]'' (1986\u20131988)\n* ''[[What a Cartoon!]]'' \u2013 featuring ''[[Dino: Stay Out!]]'' (1995) and ''[[Dino: The Great Egg-Scape]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Cave Kids]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Yabba-Dabba Dinosaurs]]'' (2020)\n\n===Films and Specials===\n* ''[[The Man Called Flintstone]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Energy: A National Issue]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[A Flintstone Christmas]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: Little Big League]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: Fred's Final Fling]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: Wind-Up Wilma]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: Jogging Fever]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[The Jetsons Meet the Flintstones]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Kids' \"Just Say No\" Special]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Hanna-Barbera's 50th: A Yabba Dabba Doo Celebration|A Yabba Dabba Doo Celebration: 50 Years of Hanna-Barbera]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[I Yabba-Dabba Do!]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Hollyrock-a-Bye Baby]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[A Flintstone Family Christmas]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[The Flintstones (film)|The Flintstones]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[A Flintstones Christmas Carol]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: On the Rocks]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[The Flintstones & WWE: Stone Age SmackDown!]]'' (2015)\n\n==Portrayal==\nDino's barks and sound effects were provided by [[Mel Blanc]] for 27 years, from 1960\u20131987; archive audio of Blanc was used for Dino in the [[The Flintstones (film)|1994 live-action film]] and [[The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas|its prequel in 2000]]. Jerry Mann provided the speaking voice of Dino in the 1961 episode \"The Snorkasaurus Hunter\". [[Frank Welker]] provided Dino's vocal effects for 20 years, from ''[[The Flintstones: Jogging Fever]]'' in 1981, until ''[[The Flintstones: On the Rocks]]'' in 2001 (a role he shared with [[Mark Mangini]]). [[Bill Farmer]] provided the vocal effects in the 2000 video game ''[[The Flintstones: Bedrock Bowling]]''. [[Mark Mangini]] shared vocal duties with Frank Welker for ''The Flintstones: On the Rocks''. In 2015, [[Eric Bauza]] provided the vocal effects for the direct-to-video ''[[The Flintstones & WWE: Stone Age SmackDown!]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{The Flintstones}}\n{{Hanna-Barbera}}\n\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 1960]]\n[[Category:Fictional dinosaurs]]\n[[Category:The Flintstones characters]]\n[[Category:Post Foods characters]]\n[[Category:Male characters in animation]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Dino (''The Flintstones'')}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color              = purple\n| name               = Dino\n| series             = [[The Flintstones]]\n| image              = Dino_from_\"The_Flintstones\".gif\n| image_size         = 150px\n| first              = The Flintstones (1960)\n| creator            = [[Hanna-Barbera]]\n| voice              = [[Mel Blanc]] (1960\u20131987, 1994, 2000)<br>Jerry Mann (1961)<br>[[Frank Welker]] (1981\u20132001)<br>[[Bill Farmer]] (2000)<br>[[Mark Mangini]] (2001)<br>[[Eric Bauza]] (2015\u2013present)\n| species            = ''Snorkasaurus''\n| spouse             = Juliet\n| gender             = Male\n| children           = 15\n}}\n'''Dino''' ({{IPAc-en|pron|\u02c8|d|i\u02d0|n|o\u028a}}) is a [[character (arts)|fictional character]] featured in the [[Hanna-Barbera]] animated [[television series]] ''[[The Flintstones]]'', and its [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]]s and [[feature film]]s. He is a pet dinosaur of the series' main characters, [[Fred Flintstone|Fred]] and [[Wilma Flintstone]].<ref>{{cite news|title= The Flintstones' 50th anniversary: 15 things you don't know|work= Daily Telegraph |date=2010-09-30|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/8034627/The-Flintstones-50th-anniversary-15-things-you-dont-know.html|accessdate=2010-10-01|location=London|first=Heidi|last=Blake}}</ref> Dino debuted in the opening credits of the pilot episode of ''The Flintstones'', but is not mentioned by name until the first season's fourth episode, \"No Help Wanted.\"\n\n==Background==\nIn the series, Dino serves the role of a pet dog, and exhibits the characteristics of a typical domesticated canine.\n\nDino is a [[prosauropod]]-like [[dinosaur]], a Snorkasaurus. Dino is a relatively small dinosaur, only slightly larger than the humans of his time, smaller than [[mammoth]]s that appear in the series, and much smaller than the numerous sauropods that appear as work animals in the series (a full-sized sauropod appears as a crane in the opening sequence, and oversized \"[[Brontosaurus|bronto]] ribs\" the size of an automobile are seen in the closing credits).\n\nA recurring gag in the series is Fred coming home from work, and Dino gets excited and knocks him down and licks his face. But no matter how hard he tries to the contrary, Fred usually gives in to Dino's ticklish and wet doglike kisses. Dino frequently exhibits human emotions, nearly \"talking,\" and can also be moved to anger, at which point he snarls and snaps, especially when Fred tries to lie either to or in front of him, which he can always tell. He also loves to play with [[Pebbles Flintstone|Pebbles]] and [[Bamm-Bamm Rubble|Bamm-Bamm]], the Flintstones' and Rubbles' respective offspring; these characters are introduced in the middle part of the series. In the episode \"Hop Happy\" Dino meets Hoppy, the Rubbles' new pet hopperoo. At first, Dino and Fred get scared, thinking he's a giant mouse, but they eventually become best friends after Hoppy helps Dino rescue their owners in an accident.\n\nAlthough he is usually immune, Dino does take a couple of brief stabs at romance.  The first comes in the episode, \"Dino Goes Hollyrock\", which originally aired on September 14, 1962.  In it, Dino falls in love with female TV star sauropod \"Sassie\" (an obvious takeoff on \"[[Lassie (1954 TV series)|Lassie]]\") and then becomes her co-star on her TV show.  However, after she removes her false eyelashes and wig, he is shocked that she turned out to be an ugly, talented sauropod that could be beautified.  The second comes in the episode, \"Dino and Juliet\", which originally aired on November 26, 1964.  In it, Dino falls in love with the new neighbor's female sauropod (Juliet).  Their romance, which results in the birth of 15 puppies, helps end the feud between Fred and the new neighbor, Mr. Loudrock.\n\nAlthough Dino had already appeared earlier in the series' first season (such as the episode \"No Help Wanted\" and \"Arthur Quarry's Dance Class\" - these episodes were made after the \"Snorkasaurus Hunter\" but aired before), Dino is portrayed quite differently in the first season's 18th episode \"The Snorkasaurus Hunter.\" In this episode, Fred and his friend [[Barney Rubble]] are on a camping trip, trying to hunt a snorkasaurus. Unlike Dino's other appearances, the snorkasaurus in this episode speaks and behaves toward Fred and Barney in a manner similar to comedian [[Phil Silvers]]. At the end of the episode, the Flintstones take in the dinosaur; the snorkasaurus (called \"Dino\" at one point by Wilma) is seen acting like a butler for the Flintstones: answering the telephone, dusting, and ironing. Dino in this episode also has purple skin instead of his varying pink-to-red color, which seems to vary from episode-to-episode during this early period, but is permanently purple after this episode. After this episode, Dino is permanently portrayed as behaving in a doglike fashion.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0580278/</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topthat.net/webrock/faq/faq10.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513034318/http://www.topthat.net/webrock/faq/faq10.htm |archivedate=2012-05-13 }}</ref>\n\nDino's origins are explained in the episode \"Dino Disappears\", which originally aired on October 10, 1963.  In it, Wilma states that Dino followed Fred home because Fred was playing with him.  Fred counters by saying he was merely trying to chase him away. This seems to refer to the episode \"Snorkasaurus Hunter\" where Fred and Barney's playing was actually hunting him down and Dino's following him was actually Dino sneaking onto the car.\n\nPost-original series, Dino appears in most of the series' spinoffs, except during the first season of ''[[The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show]]''. There, Dino is replaced by Wooly, a dwarf mammoth, as the Flintstone family's pet. However, starting with the following series' ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Hour]]'', Dino once again becomes a regular character.\n\nIn the 1980-1982 series ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Show (1980 TV series)|The Flintstone Comedy Show]]'', Dino is featured in his own segment, \"[[The Flintstone Comedy Show (1980 TV series)#Dino and Cavemouse|Dino and Cavemouse]],\" where Dino tries futilely to capture a pesky [[mouse]] in the Flintstone household. The segments bear some similarities to classic cat-and-mouse cartoons such as ''[[Tom and Jerry]]''. Dino later appears as a puppy in 1986-1988 series ''[[The Flintstone Kids]]'' (including his own segment, \"Dino's Dilemmas\"), as Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm's babysitter in the short-lived 1996 series ''[[Cave Kids]]'', and also starred in his own two 7-minute short cartoons, ''[[Dino: Stay Out!]]'' (1995) and ''[[Dino: The Great Egg-Scape]]'' (1997).\n\n==Other media==\n[[File:Dino Harikalar Diyari Flintstones 06029 nevit.jpg|thumbnail|right|Dino statue (right), along with [[Fred Flintstone]] (left).]]\nDino appears in both live-action movies. He isn't seen very often in the first film, 1994's ''[[The Flintstones (film)|The Flintstones]]''. Dino was created with both computer-generated imagery and as a puppet from [[Jim Henson's Creature Shop]], while archival audio from the original series was used to serve as Dino's voice.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nHowever, in the second film, 2000's ''[[The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas]]'', Dino has more screen time; he appears here as a puppy. Fred won Dino's egg as a prize after winning a carnival game. Initially, Fred didn't think much of the egg as he felt that the creatures inside never live long. On a [[Ferris wheel]], just as Fred and Wilma are about to kiss, Dino's egg hatches and he takes an immediate attachment to Fred, believing him to be his mother. (This, of course, contradicts Dino's origin in the original series.)\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television shows===\n* ''[[The Flintstones]]'' (1960\u20131966)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Hour]]'' (1972\u20131974)\n* ''[[Fred Flintstone and Friends]]'' (1977\u20131978)\n* ''[[The New Fred and Barney Show]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Thing]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo]]'' (1979\u20131980)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Show]]'' (1980\u20131982)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Funnies]]'' (1982\u20131984)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Kids]]'' (1986\u20131988)\n* ''[[Cave Kids]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Yabba-Dabba Dinosaurs]]'' (2020)\n\n===Films and Specials===\n* ''[[The Man Called Flintstone]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Energy: A National Issue]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[A Flintstone Christmas]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: Little Big League]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: Fred's Final Fling]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: Wind-Up Wilma]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: Jogging Fever]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[The Jetsons Meet the Flintstones]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Kids' \"Just Say No\" Special]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Hanna-Barbera's 50th: A Yabba Dabba Doo Celebration|A Yabba Dabba Doo Celebration: 50 Years of Hanna-Barbera]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[I Yabba-Dabba Do!]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Hollyrock-a-Bye Baby]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[A Flintstone Family Christmas]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[The Flintstones (film)|The Flintstones]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[A Flintstones Christmas Carol]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[The Flintstones: On the Rocks]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[The Flintstones & WWE: Stone Age SmackDown!]]'' (2015)\n\n==Portrayal==\nDino's barks and sound effects were provided by [[Mel Blanc]] for 27 years, from 1960\u20131987; archive audio of Blanc was used for Dino in the [[The Flintstones (film)|1994 live-action film]] and [[The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas|its prequel in 2000]]. Jerry Mann provided the speaking voice of Dino in the 1961 episode \"The Snorkasaurus Hunter\". [[Frank Welker]] provided Dino's vocal effects for 20 years, from ''[[The Flintstones: Jogging Fever]]'' in 1981, until ''[[The Flintstones: On the Rocks]]'' in 2001 (a role he shared with [[Mark Mangini]]). [[Bill Farmer]] provided the vocal effects in the 2000 video game ''[[The Flintstones: Bedrock Bowling]]''. [[Mark Mangini]] shared vocal duties with Frank Welker for ''The Flintstones: On the Rocks''. In 2015, [[Eric Bauza]] provided the vocal effects for the direct-to-video ''[[The Flintstones & WWE: Stone Age SmackDown!]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{The Flintstones}}\n{{Hanna-Barbera}}\n\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 1960]]\n[[Category:Fictional dinosaurs]]\n[[Category:The Flintstones characters]]\n[[Category:Post Foods characters]]\n[[Category:Male characters in animation]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision shows", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dino_(The_Flintstones)"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kenya", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Kenya}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Kenyan English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kenya\n| map1            = File:Kenya_corona_county_map_26032020.png\n| legend1         = {{center|Map of counties with confirmed COVID-19 cases in Kenya {{As of|alt=as of 3 April 2020|2020|04|03}}.}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Kenya]]\n| first_case      = [[Nairobi]]\n| arrival_date    = 13 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=13|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], China\n| recovery_cases  = 53\n| deaths          = 11\n| confirmed_cases = 246<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/citizentvkenya/status/1251061504444715008 |title=BREAKING: Kenya confirms 12 more COVID-19 cases bringing total number to 246. Health CS Mutahi Kagwe says 5 of them are hotel workers.pic.twitter.com/5mmlIuBapt |last=Kenya |first=Citizen TV |date=2020-04-17 |website=@citizentvkenya |language=en |access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|http://www.health.go.ke}}\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] reached [[Kenya]] in March 2020 with the initial cases reported in [[Nairobi]] and [[Kajiado]] Counties.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Kenya medical cases chart}}\n\n===March 2020===\nOn 13 March, the first case in Kenya, a 27-year-old Kenyan woman who traveled from the [[the United States|US]] via [[London]], was confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya-confirms-first-coronavirus-case/1056-5489268-28tqll/index.html|title=Kenya confirms first coronavirus case - VIDEO|website=[[Daily Nation]]|date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The Kenyan government identified and isolated a number of people who had come into contact with the first case.\n\nOn 15 March, [[Cabinet of Kenya|Cabinet Secretary]] for Health, [[Mutahi Kagwe]], announced that two people who had sat next to the initial patient on the aircraft in transit from the United States had also tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.capitalfm.co.ke/news/2020/03/kenya-coronavirus-cases-rises-to-3/|title=Kenya coronavirus cases rises to 3 |work=Capital News |date=15 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 15 March 2020, President Uhuru Kenyatta directed that the following measures to curb COVID-19 be implemented:\n\n* \"Travel from any countries with any case of Corona virus be restricted.\n* \"Only Kenyan Citizens, and any foreigners with valid residence permits will be allowed to come into the country provided they proceed on self quarantine or to a government designated quarantine facility.\n* \"All schools and higher learning institutions be closed by Friday March 20, 2020.\n* \"Government and businesses people start working from home; except essential services.\n* \"Cashless transactions over cash. Cost of transactions reduced.\n* \"No congressional meetings \u2013 weddings, malls, night clubs, churches, limitation of visits to hospitals.\n* \"Hospitals and Shopping malls to give soap and water/hand sanitizers, and regular cleaning of facilities.\n* \"Cargo vessels, aircraft or ships can come into the country provided they are disinfected at point of departure and the crew quarantined on arrival.\n* \"UN Headquarters in Kenya  continue operating diplomats travelling to the UN are also exempted from the travel restrictions but observe the self-quarantine rule.\n* \"A toll-free number (719) set up to report suspected coronavirus cases.\"<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.health.go.ke/kenya-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-four-cs-health/|title=Kenya coronavirus cases rise to four, CS health \u2013 MINISTRY OF HEALTH|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nThe Health Minister Mutahi Kagwe banned all social gatherings including religious gatherings on the same date. All flights were banned effective Wednesday 25 March by the Health CS.\n\nOn 16 March, the government through its spokesman Col [[Cyrus Oguna]] said on an update that there were another three people who were suspected to be carriers of the virus and that their results were to be released soon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya-reports-3-suspected-virus-cases/1056-5493300-10wucliz/index.html|work=Nation news |title=Kenya reports 3 suspected virus cases |date=16 March 2020 |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, it was announced by the Health Secretary that a fourth case had been diagnosed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-four/1056-5494400-16rhfez/index.html|title=Kenya coronavirus cases rise to four|website=Daily Nation|language=en|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> On 18 March, three more cases confirmed were by the Health Secretary, bringing the total confirmed cases in Kenya to seven.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalfm.co.ke/news/2020/03/health-ministry-confirms-3-more-coronavirus-cases/|title=Health Ministry Confirms 3 More Coronavirus Cases|last=|first=|date=18 March 2020|website=capitalfm.co.ke|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, eight more cases were confirmed by the Health Secretary, bringing the total cases confirmed to 15. The government confirmed it was tracing 363 people who are believed to have had contact with the eight new cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nairobinews.nation.co.ke/news/number-of-coronavirus-cases-jumps-to-15-after-eight-more-test-positive|title=Number of coronavirus cases jumps to 15 after eight more test positive|website=Nairobi News|language=en-US|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, another case was confirmed bringing the total confirmed cases to 16.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-16-Mutahi-Kagwe/1056-5501490-4nbovnz/index.html|title=Kenya coronavirus cases rise to 16|website=Daily Nation|language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, nine more cases reported for a total of 25 nationally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/health/article/2001365520/coronavirus-kenya-cases-rise-to-25-after-nine-more-people-test-positive|website=www.standardmedia.co.ke|title=Coronavirus: Kenya cases rise to 25 after nine more people test positive|access-date=25 March 2020}}\n</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, the first recovery was confirmed, and three more cases were recorded, bringing the total confirmed cases to 28.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya-announces-first-coronavirus-recovery/1056-5504166-tda1qd/index.html|title=Kenya announces first coronavirus recovery|website=Daily Nation|language=en|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalfm.co.ke/news/2020/03/kenyas-first-covid-19-patient-recovers-as-3-more-cases-recorded-raising-caseload-to-28/|title=Kenya's First COVID-19 Patient Recovers As 3 More Cases Recorded Raising Caseload To 28|website=CapitalFM|date=25 March 2020|language=en|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, three more cases were recorded and bringing the total confirmed cases to 31. In addition to Nairobi, the government confirmed that corona virus cases in Kenya are spread among four other counties, namely [[Kajiado County|Kajiado]], [[Mombasa County|Mombasa]], [[Kilifi County|Kilifi]], and [[Kwale County|Kwale]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/health/article/2001365802/covid-19-three-more-cases-confirmed-bringing-total-to-31|title=Coronavirus: Kenya confirms three more cases bringing total to 31 |language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> On the same date, the first death of a person infected with the corona virus was reported in Kenya. The patient was a 66-year-old Kenyan man who had recently returned from a business trip in [[Eswatini]] and had transited via [[O. R. Tambo International Airport]] in [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]]. It is unknown where exactly he contracted the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-star.co.ke/covid-19/2020-03-26-first-kenyan-dies-of-covid-19-cs-kagwe/|title=First Kenyan dies of Covid-19 - CS Kagwe|author=Claire Munde|website=The Star|language=en-KE|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, the ministry of health confirmed 7 more cases, bringing a total tally of confirmed covid-19 cases in Kenya to 38. On the same day, the government announced that 2 patients who had earlier tested positive had tested negative and were awaiting for a second test to confirm they had fully recovered.\n\nOn 29 March, four more cases were recorded bringing the total confirmed cases to 42.During a briefing on Sunday, Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe said of the four, one is a Kenyan, one American, one Cameroonian and one a Burkinab\u00e9. Mr Kagwe said three of the cases were based in Nairobi and one in Mombasa. The CS said of the 42 cases, 24 are male while 18 are females. Nairobi leads with 31 cases followed by Kilifi (six), Mombasa (Three) and Kwale and Kajiado one each.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Four-more-test-positive-for-Covid-19-/1056-5508262-mkqe0ez/index.html|title=COVID-19: Kenya announces 4 new corona virus cases|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, Kenya's coronavirus cases have risen by 8, with the total now standing at 50 that have been confirmed, Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe on Monday said that of the eight  confirmed cases, six were based in Nairobi, one in Kitui and one in Mombasa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya-coronavirus-cases-rise-by-8-to-hit-50/1056-5508982-m3lx3t/index.html|title=COVID-19: Kenya announces 4 new corona virus cases|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, Kenya's coronavirus cases rose by 9, bringing the total to 59 confirmed cases to date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya-Coronavirus-Tuesday-Update-/1056-5509758-dd873pz/index.html|title=Nine more test positive for coronavirus|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\n\nOn April 1, Kenya's coronavirus cases rose by 22, bringing the total to 81 confirmed cases to  date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya\u2013coronavirus\u2013Wednesday\u2013update\u2013/1056\u20135509758\u2013dd873pz/index.html|title=Twenty two more test positive for coronavirus|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> Additionally, the Kenyan government confirmed that the first and third reported cases had both full recovered from the virus, bringing the total number of recoveries nationally to three. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/health/article/2001366493/coronavirus-cases-in-kenya-jump-to-81l|title=Kenya coronavirus cases increase to 81 after 22 test positive |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, an additional 29 cases were confirmed bringing the total number of cases to 110 nationally. The government reported one more recovered patient increasing the total recoveries to four. Additionally, two more deaths were confirmed, one from Nairobi and the one in Mombasa, bringing the total number of deaths due to coronavirus to three.\n\nOn April 4th 4 more cases were recorded out of a total sample of 325 cases.\n\nOn April 6th president Uhuru Kenyatta announced a cessation of movement in and out of The Nairobi Metropolitan Area for a containment period of 21 days, other counties affected by the cessation are; Mombasa and Kilifi and Kwale county that would take effect as from 8th April \n\nOn April 7th, CS Mutahi Kagwe announced 14 more cases bringing the total to 172 people. \u2014 with the virus. The numbers keep rising and rising.\nHe also announced that 4 more people recovered from the virus bringing the total recoveries to 7.\n\nOn 8th April, the number of people with coronavirus increased by 14 confirmed cases as announced by the Health Secretary, bringing the total number to 179.\n\nOn 9th April, the health cabinet secretary announced an increase in number of confirmed cases by 5 bringing the total number of people with the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|Novel Coronavirus]] to 184. He also announced an increase in number of deaths to 7.\n\nOn 10 April, 5 more cases of people who tested positive for the Coronavirus were confirmed as announced by the health secretary, bringing the total number of the confirmed cases to 189, it was also announced that 10 patients who had tested positive for Coronavirus have tested negative and are awaiting to be discharged from Mbangathi hospital, bringing the recovery cases to 22.\n\nOn 13 April, the total number of cases was announced to have reached 208, with a total of 9 deaths and 40 discharged-and-recovered.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MOH_Kenya/status/1249698220806111234|author=Kenya Ministry of Health|title=COVID-19 Update|date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April, the total number of cases was announced to have reached 225, with a total of 10 deaths and 53 discharged-and-recovered.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/DailyNation/videos/621155368435281/|author=Daily Nation|title=9 more test positive for COVID-19 bringing the total 225, one more death reported|date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 15, 2019, the Kenyan Ministry of Health reported 9 new cases increasing the total number of cases to 225, 12 new recoveries thus increasing the number of total recoveries to 53. The Ministry also reported 1 new fatality, increasing the total number of fatalities to 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MOH_Kenya/status/1250395809717379073|author=Kenya Ministry of Health|title=Coronavirus Update|date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n2366 people had been tested as of April 15, 2020, 1911 people had been released after testing negative and 455 people were still subject to follow up according to statistics provided by the Kenyan Ministry of Health.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MOH_Kenya/status/1250395809717379073|author=Kenya Ministry of Health|title=Coronavirus Update|date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\nIn response to the rise of corona virus cases in Kenya to three, on 15 March the government of Kenya closed all schools and directed that all public and private sector workers work from home, wherever possible.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/scienceandhealth/Coronavirus-update-Kenya/3073694-5492136-splkgfz/index.html|title=Coronavirus: Kenya confirms 2 more cases|website=The East African|language=en|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Travel restrictions were later imposed to prevent non-residents from entry. Kenyan nationals and residents were required to self-quarantine for a minimum of fourteen days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/kenya-blocks-entry-residents-virus-response-200315154944348.html|title=Kenya blocks entry for non-residents in virus response|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, following the confirmation of an additional eight cases, bringing the total to 16 nationally, the Kenyan government introduced additional measures and directives to reduce the spread of coronavirus in the country. These measures included a suspension of all international flights effective at midnight on 25 March, with the exception of cargo flights (all persons entering the country will be compelled to undergo quarantine at a government facility). The government further stipulated that any persons, including senior government officials, found to be in violation of quarantine measures would be forcefully quarantind at their own expense. All bars were to remain closed from 22 March, with restaurants allowed to remain open for takeaway services only. All public service vehicles (i.e., [[matatu]]s and buses) had to adhere to passenger-distancing guidelines previously stipulated on 20 March. Further, all public gatherings at churches, mosques, funerals and elsewhere were restricted to no more than 15 people, and weddings were banned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kenya-today.com/news/breaking-8-new-coronavirus-cases-search-for-363-persons-who-had-contact-with-victims-continues|title=8 new Coronavirus cases, search for 363 persons who had contact with victims continues|website=www.kenya-today.com|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Economic response===\n\nOn 25 March, [[President of Kenya|President]] [[Uhuru Kenyatta]], following the reporting of an additional three cases, announced a nation-wide curfew on unauthorized movement from 7pm to 5am beginning on Friday, 27 March. The government also unveiled measures to buffer Kenyans against financial hardships arising movement restrictions associated with the coronavirus crisis, including:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.k24tv.co.ke/news/tax-relief-crb-listing-suspension-here-are-all-directives-issued-by-pres-kenyatta-to-ensure-you-have-more-money-in-your-pocket-18275/?utm_source=website&utm_medium=coronavirus&utm_campaign=coronavirus&utm_term=coronavirus|website=www.k24tv.co.ke|title=Tax relief, CRB-listing suspension: Here are all directives issued by Pres. Kenyatta to ensure you have more money in your pocket|date=25 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n*100% tax relief to Kenyans earning KSh 24,000 (US$228) and below.\n*Pay as you earn ([[Kenyan taxation system|PAYE]]) reduction from a maximum of 30% to 25%.\n*Reduction of turnover tax rate from 3% to 1% for all micro, small and medium enterprises.\n*Reduction of resident income tax to 25%.\n*Making available KSh 10 billion (US$95 million) to vulnerable groups including the elderly and orphans, among others. \n*Temporary suspension of the listing of loan defaulters for of any person, micro, small and medium enterprise and corporate entities whose loan account is in arrears effective 1 April 2020.\n*Reduction of VAT from 16% to 14% effective 1 April 2020.\n\nThe government also moved to increase the allocation of funds for health care, along with other fiscal adjustments to the economy:\n*KSh 1 billion (US$9.5 million) from the Universal Health Coverage kitty to be channelled to the employment of new health workers to help combat the spread of COVID-19.\n*The President and Deputy President to take 80% pay-cut, all Cabinet Secretaries to take 30% pay-cuts, Chief Administrative Secretaries (30%) and Principal Secretaries (20%).\n*All State and public officers aged 50 and above; and have preexisting medical conditions, to take leave from work, or be allowed to work from home. This directive excludes those public officers working in the security department.\n*[[Central Bank of Kenya]] to lower the Central Bank Rate from 8.25% to 7.25%.\n*Reduce the Cash Reserve Ratio from 5.25% to 4.25% to increase liquidity of KSh 35 billion to [[List of banks in Kenya|commercial banks]], which, in turn, will be in positions to provide loan services to \u201cdistressed Kenyans\u201d.\n\n===Nationwide curfew and police response===\nThe 7pm \u2013 5am curfew announced on 25 March was accompanied by reports of [[police brutality]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2001366037/sticks-stones-and-broken-bones-in-first-curfew-night|website=www.standardmedia.co.ke|title=Sticks, stones and broken bones in first curfew night  |date=28 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> First-hand accounts and video footage in several cities, including [[Nairobi]] and [[Mombasa]], indicated that police used beatings and tear gas on 27 March. Some accounts indicate that detention resulted in crowding of people into small areas, contrary to the curfew's goal of increasing social distancing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/kenyas-coronavirus-curfew-begins-with-wave-of-police-crackdowns/2020/03/28/358327aa-7064-11ea-a156-0048b62cdb51_story.html|website=www.washingtonpost.com|title=Kenya's coronavirus curfew begins with wave of police crackdowns |date=28 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> Kenyan officials and government outlets later condemned police behaviour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2001365989/stop-beating-kenyans-during-curfew-leaders-tell-police|website=www.standardmedia.co.ke|title=Stop bludgeoning Kenyans during curfew, leaders tell police |date=28 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently, a petition was filed by [[Law Society of Kenya]] claiming that the curfew itself was [[unconstitutional]], \"because it is blanket and indefinite, and because it is ultra vires [it contravenes] the Public Order Act\" and that the curfew posed a threat to the health of the general population. The petition further asserted that, \"police recklessly horded large crowds on the ground, contrary to WHO advice on social distancing. Moreover, the first respondent (police) stopped the media from monitoring their movement and assaulted journalists covering the process\". <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2001366258/lsk-wants-curfew-declared-illegal-or-delayed-to-10pm|website=www.standardmedia.co.ke|title=LSK wants curfew declared illegal or delayed to 10pm |date=30 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\nOn March 30, the [[High Court of Kenya]] upheld the curfew itself, but barred police from using excessive force to enforce the curfew  and demanded the police provide guidelines for observing the curfew. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2001366267/court-bars-police-from-using-excessive-force-during-curfew|website=www.standardmedia.co.ke|title=Court bars police from using excessive force during curfew|date=30 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, a 13-year-old boy was shot dead, allegedly by police, on the balcony of his home in Kiamaiko, Nairobi, 20 minutes after the curfew had started.<ref>{{cite web |title=Family distraught after teenager allegedly shot by police dies |url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Boy13-allegedly-shot-by-police-dies-/1056-5509816-c80fb8z/index.html |publisher=Daily Nation}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nThe travel restrictions reduced Kenya's hotel, tourism and [[Kenya Flower Council|flower]] industries. In contrast to citizens in [[Developed country|industrialized countries]], some Kenyans have the ability to switch from their city jobs to rural labour for food.<ref>{{cite web |title=#594 \u2014 The Economic Impact of Coronavirus on Kenya \u2013 Reports from Kenya |url=http://davidzarembka.com/2020/03/27/594-the-economic-impact-of-coronavirus-on-kenya/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328220959/http://davidzarembka.com/2020/03/27/594-the-economic-impact-of-coronavirus-on-kenya/ |archivedate=28 March 2020 |date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Kenya|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Kenya|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Kenya]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|Kenya]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Kenya]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Kenya}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Kenyan English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kenya\n| map1            = File:Kenya_corona_county_map_26032020.png\n| legend1         = {{center|Map of counties with confirmed COVID-19 cases in Kenya {{As of|alt=as of 3 April 2020|2020|04|03}}.}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Kenya]]\n| first_case      = [[Nairobi]]\n| arrival_date    = 13 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=13|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], China\n| recovery_cases  = 53\n| deaths          = 12\n| confirmed_cases = 246<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/citizentvkenya/status/1251061504444715008 |title=BREAKING: Kenya confirms 12 more COVID-19 cases bringing total number to 246. Health CS Mutahi Kagwe says 5 of them are hotel workers.pic.twitter.com/5mmlIuBapt |last=Kenya |first=Citizen TV |date=2020-04-17 |website=@citizentvkenya |language=en |access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|http://www.health.go.ke}}\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] reached [[Kenya]] in March 2020 with the initial cases reported in [[Nairobi]] and [[Kajiado]] Counties.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Kenya medical cases chart}}\n\n===March 2020===\nOn 13 March, the first case in Kenya, a 27-year-old Kenyan woman who traveled from the [[the United States|US]] via [[London]], was confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya-confirms-first-coronavirus-case/1056-5489268-28tqll/index.html|title=Kenya confirms first coronavirus case - VIDEO|website=[[Daily Nation]]|date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The Kenyan government identified and isolated a number of people who had come into contact with the first case.\n\nOn 15 March, [[Cabinet of Kenya|Cabinet Secretary]] for Health, [[Mutahi Kagwe]], announced that two people who had sat next to the initial patient on the aircraft in transit from the United States had also tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.capitalfm.co.ke/news/2020/03/kenya-coronavirus-cases-rises-to-3/|title=Kenya coronavirus cases rises to 3 |work=Capital News |date=15 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 15 March 2020, President Uhuru Kenyatta directed that the following measures to curb COVID-19 be implemented:\n\n* \"Travel from any countries with any case of Corona virus be restricted.\n* \"Only Kenyan Citizens, and any foreigners with valid residence permits will be allowed to come into the country provided they proceed on self quarantine or to a government designated quarantine facility.\n* \"All schools and higher learning institutions be closed by Friday March 20, 2020.\n* \"Government and businesses people start working from home; except essential services.\n* \"Cashless transactions over cash. Cost of transactions reduced.\n* \"No congressional meetings \u2013 weddings, malls, night clubs, churches, limitation of visits to hospitals.\n* \"Hospitals and Shopping malls to give soap and water/hand sanitizers, and regular cleaning of facilities.\n* \"Cargo vessels, aircraft or ships can come into the country provided they are disinfected at point of departure and the crew quarantined on arrival.\n* \"UN Headquarters in Kenya  continue operating diplomats travelling to the UN are also exempted from the travel restrictions but observe the self-quarantine rule.\n* \"A toll-free number (719) set up to report suspected coronavirus cases.\"<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.health.go.ke/kenya-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-four-cs-health/|title=Kenya coronavirus cases rise to four, CS health \u2013 MINISTRY OF HEALTH|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nThe Health Minister Mutahi Kagwe banned all social gatherings including religious gatherings on the same date. All flights were banned effective Wednesday 25 March by the Health CS.\n\nOn 16 March, the government through its spokesman Col [[Cyrus Oguna]] said on an update that there were another three people who were suspected to be carriers of the virus and that their results were to be released soon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya-reports-3-suspected-virus-cases/1056-5493300-10wucliz/index.html|work=Nation news |title=Kenya reports 3 suspected virus cases |date=16 March 2020 |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, it was announced by the Health Secretary that a fourth case had been diagnosed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-four/1056-5494400-16rhfez/index.html|title=Kenya coronavirus cases rise to four|website=Daily Nation|language=en|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> On 18 March, three more cases confirmed were by the Health Secretary, bringing the total confirmed cases in Kenya to seven.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalfm.co.ke/news/2020/03/health-ministry-confirms-3-more-coronavirus-cases/|title=Health Ministry Confirms 3 More Coronavirus Cases|last=|first=|date=18 March 2020|website=capitalfm.co.ke|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, eight more cases were confirmed by the Health Secretary, bringing the total cases confirmed to 15. The government confirmed it was tracing 363 people who are believed to have had contact with the eight new cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nairobinews.nation.co.ke/news/number-of-coronavirus-cases-jumps-to-15-after-eight-more-test-positive|title=Number of coronavirus cases jumps to 15 after eight more test positive|website=Nairobi News|language=en-US|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, another case was confirmed bringing the total confirmed cases to 16.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-16-Mutahi-Kagwe/1056-5501490-4nbovnz/index.html|title=Kenya coronavirus cases rise to 16|website=Daily Nation|language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, nine more cases reported for a total of 25 nationally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/health/article/2001365520/coronavirus-kenya-cases-rise-to-25-after-nine-more-people-test-positive|website=www.standardmedia.co.ke|title=Coronavirus: Kenya cases rise to 25 after nine more people test positive|access-date=25 March 2020}}\n</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, the first recovery was confirmed, and three more cases were recorded, bringing the total confirmed cases to 28.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya-announces-first-coronavirus-recovery/1056-5504166-tda1qd/index.html|title=Kenya announces first coronavirus recovery|website=Daily Nation|language=en|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalfm.co.ke/news/2020/03/kenyas-first-covid-19-patient-recovers-as-3-more-cases-recorded-raising-caseload-to-28/|title=Kenya's First COVID-19 Patient Recovers As 3 More Cases Recorded Raising Caseload To 28|website=CapitalFM|date=25 March 2020|language=en|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, three more cases were recorded and bringing the total confirmed cases to 31. In addition to Nairobi, the government confirmed that corona virus cases in Kenya are spread among four other counties, namely [[Kajiado County|Kajiado]], [[Mombasa County|Mombasa]], [[Kilifi County|Kilifi]], and [[Kwale County|Kwale]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/health/article/2001365802/covid-19-three-more-cases-confirmed-bringing-total-to-31|title=Coronavirus: Kenya confirms three more cases bringing total to 31 |language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> On the same date, the first death of a person infected with the corona virus was reported in Kenya. The patient was a 66-year-old Kenyan man who had recently returned from a business trip in [[Eswatini]] and had transited via [[O. R. Tambo International Airport]] in [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]]. It is unknown where exactly he contracted the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-star.co.ke/covid-19/2020-03-26-first-kenyan-dies-of-covid-19-cs-kagwe/|title=First Kenyan dies of Covid-19 - CS Kagwe|author=Claire Munde|website=The Star|language=en-KE|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, the ministry of health confirmed 7 more cases, bringing a total tally of confirmed covid-19 cases in Kenya to 38. On the same day, the government announced that 2 patients who had earlier tested positive had tested negative and were awaiting for a second test to confirm they had fully recovered.\n\nOn 29 March, four more cases were recorded bringing the total confirmed cases to 42.During a briefing on Sunday, Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe said of the four, one is a Kenyan, one American, one Cameroonian and one a Burkinab\u00e9. Mr Kagwe said three of the cases were based in Nairobi and one in Mombasa. The CS said of the 42 cases, 24 are male while 18 are females. Nairobi leads with 31 cases followed by Kilifi (six), Mombasa (Three) and Kwale and Kajiado one each.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Four-more-test-positive-for-Covid-19-/1056-5508262-mkqe0ez/index.html|title=COVID-19: Kenya announces 4 new corona virus cases|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, Kenya's coronavirus cases have risen by 8, with the total now standing at 50 that have been confirmed, Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe on Monday said that of the eight  confirmed cases, six were based in Nairobi, one in Kitui and one in Mombasa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya-coronavirus-cases-rise-by-8-to-hit-50/1056-5508982-m3lx3t/index.html|title=COVID-19: Kenya announces 4 new corona virus cases|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, Kenya's coronavirus cases rose by 9, bringing the total to 59 confirmed cases to date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya-Coronavirus-Tuesday-Update-/1056-5509758-dd873pz/index.html|title=Nine more test positive for coronavirus|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\n\nOn April 1, Kenya's coronavirus cases rose by 22, bringing the total to 81 confirmed cases to  date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya\u2013coronavirus\u2013Wednesday\u2013update\u2013/1056\u20135509758\u2013dd873pz/index.html|title=Twenty two more test positive for coronavirus|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> Additionally, the Kenyan government confirmed that the first and third reported cases had both full recovered from the virus, bringing the total number of recoveries nationally to three. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/health/article/2001366493/coronavirus-cases-in-kenya-jump-to-81l|title=Kenya coronavirus cases increase to 81 after 22 test positive |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, an additional 29 cases were confirmed bringing the total number of cases to 110 nationally. The government reported one more recovered patient increasing the total recoveries to four. Additionally, two more deaths were confirmed, one from Nairobi and the one in Mombasa, bringing the total number of deaths due to coronavirus to three.\n\nOn April 4th 4 more cases were recorded out of a total sample of 325 cases.\n\nOn April 6th president Uhuru Kenyatta announced a cessation of movement in and out of The Nairobi Metropolitan Area for a containment period of 21 days, other counties affected by the cessation are; Mombasa and Kilifi and Kwale county that would take effect as from 8th April \n\nOn April 7th, CS Mutahi Kagwe announced 14 more cases bringing the total to 172 people. \u2014 with the virus. The numbers keep rising and rising.\nHe also announced that 4 more people recovered from the virus bringing the total recoveries to 7.\n\nOn 8th April, the number of people with coronavirus increased by 14 confirmed cases as announced by the Health Secretary, bringing the total number to 179.\n\nOn 9th April, the health cabinet secretary announced an increase in number of confirmed cases by 5 bringing the total number of people with the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|Novel Coronavirus]] to 184. He also announced an increase in number of deaths to 7.\n\nOn 10 April, 5 more cases of people who tested positive for the Coronavirus were confirmed as announced by the health secretary, bringing the total number of the confirmed cases to 189, it was also announced that 10 patients who had tested positive for Coronavirus have tested negative and are awaiting to be discharged from Mbangathi hospital, bringing the recovery cases to 22.\n\nOn 13 April, the total number of cases was announced to have reached 208, with a total of 9 deaths and 40 discharged-and-recovered.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MOH_Kenya/status/1249698220806111234|author=Kenya Ministry of Health|title=COVID-19 Update|date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April, the total number of cases was announced to have reached 225, with a total of 10 deaths and 53 discharged-and-recovered.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/DailyNation/videos/621155368435281/|author=Daily Nation|title=9 more test positive for COVID-19 bringing the total 225, one more death reported|date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 15, 2019, the Kenyan Ministry of Health reported 9 new cases increasing the total number of cases to 225, 12 new recoveries thus increasing the number of total recoveries to 53. The Ministry also reported 1 new fatality, increasing the total number of fatalities to 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MOH_Kenya/status/1250395809717379073|author=Kenya Ministry of Health|title=Coronavirus Update|date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n2366 people had been tested as of April 15, 2020, 1911 people had been released after testing negative and 455 people were still subject to follow up according to statistics provided by the Kenyan Ministry of Health.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MOH_Kenya/status/1250395809717379073|author=Kenya Ministry of Health|title=Coronavirus Update|date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\nIn response to the rise of corona virus cases in Kenya to three, on 15 March the government of Kenya closed all schools and directed that all public and private sector workers work from home, wherever possible.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/scienceandhealth/Coronavirus-update-Kenya/3073694-5492136-splkgfz/index.html|title=Coronavirus: Kenya confirms 2 more cases|website=The East African|language=en|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Travel restrictions were later imposed to prevent non-residents from entry. Kenyan nationals and residents were required to self-quarantine for a minimum of fourteen days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/kenya-blocks-entry-residents-virus-response-200315154944348.html|title=Kenya blocks entry for non-residents in virus response|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, following the confirmation of an additional eight cases, bringing the total to 16 nationally, the Kenyan government introduced additional measures and directives to reduce the spread of coronavirus in the country. These measures included a suspension of all international flights effective at midnight on 25 March, with the exception of cargo flights (all persons entering the country will be compelled to undergo quarantine at a government facility). The government further stipulated that any persons, including senior government officials, found to be in violation of quarantine measures would be forcefully quarantind at their own expense. All bars were to remain closed from 22 March, with restaurants allowed to remain open for takeaway services only. All public service vehicles (i.e., [[matatu]]s and buses) had to adhere to passenger-distancing guidelines previously stipulated on 20 March. Further, all public gatherings at churches, mosques, funerals and elsewhere were restricted to no more than 15 people, and weddings were banned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kenya-today.com/news/breaking-8-new-coronavirus-cases-search-for-363-persons-who-had-contact-with-victims-continues|title=8 new Coronavirus cases, search for 363 persons who had contact with victims continues|website=www.kenya-today.com|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Economic response===\n\nOn 25 March, [[President of Kenya|President]] [[Uhuru Kenyatta]], following the reporting of an additional three cases, announced a nation-wide curfew on unauthorized movement from 7pm to 5am beginning on Friday, 27 March. The government also unveiled measures to buffer Kenyans against financial hardships arising movement restrictions associated with the coronavirus crisis, including:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.k24tv.co.ke/news/tax-relief-crb-listing-suspension-here-are-all-directives-issued-by-pres-kenyatta-to-ensure-you-have-more-money-in-your-pocket-18275/?utm_source=website&utm_medium=coronavirus&utm_campaign=coronavirus&utm_term=coronavirus|website=www.k24tv.co.ke|title=Tax relief, CRB-listing suspension: Here are all directives issued by Pres. Kenyatta to ensure you have more money in your pocket|date=25 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n*100% tax relief to Kenyans earning KSh 24,000 (US$228) and below.\n*Pay as you earn ([[Kenyan taxation system|PAYE]]) reduction from a maximum of 30% to 25%.\n*Reduction of turnover tax rate from 3% to 1% for all micro, small and medium enterprises.\n*Reduction of resident income tax to 25%.\n*Making available KSh 10 billion (US$95 million) to vulnerable groups including the elderly and orphans, among others. \n*Temporary suspension of the listing of loan defaulters for of any person, micro, small and medium enterprise and corporate entities whose loan account is in arrears effective 1 April 2020.\n*Reduction of VAT from 16% to 14% effective 1 April 2020.\n\nThe government also moved to increase the allocation of funds for health care, along with other fiscal adjustments to the economy:\n*KSh 1 billion (US$9.5 million) from the Universal Health Coverage kitty to be channelled to the employment of new health workers to help combat the spread of COVID-19.\n*The President and Deputy President to take 80% pay-cut, all Cabinet Secretaries to take 30% pay-cuts, Chief Administrative Secretaries (30%) and Principal Secretaries (20%).\n*All State and public officers aged 50 and above; and have preexisting medical conditions, to take leave from work, or be allowed to work from home. This directive excludes those public officers working in the security department.\n*[[Central Bank of Kenya]] to lower the Central Bank Rate from 8.25% to 7.25%.\n*Reduce the Cash Reserve Ratio from 5.25% to 4.25% to increase liquidity of KSh 35 billion to [[List of banks in Kenya|commercial banks]], which, in turn, will be in positions to provide loan services to \u201cdistressed Kenyans\u201d.\n\n===Nationwide curfew and police response===\nThe 7pm \u2013 5am curfew announced on 25 March was accompanied by reports of [[police brutality]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2001366037/sticks-stones-and-broken-bones-in-first-curfew-night|website=www.standardmedia.co.ke|title=Sticks, stones and broken bones in first curfew night  |date=28 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> First-hand accounts and video footage in several cities, including [[Nairobi]] and [[Mombasa]], indicated that police used beatings and tear gas on 27 March. Some accounts indicate that detention resulted in crowding of people into small areas, contrary to the curfew's goal of increasing social distancing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/kenyas-coronavirus-curfew-begins-with-wave-of-police-crackdowns/2020/03/28/358327aa-7064-11ea-a156-0048b62cdb51_story.html|website=www.washingtonpost.com|title=Kenya's coronavirus curfew begins with wave of police crackdowns |date=28 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> Kenyan officials and government outlets later condemned police behaviour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2001365989/stop-beating-kenyans-during-curfew-leaders-tell-police|website=www.standardmedia.co.ke|title=Stop bludgeoning Kenyans during curfew, leaders tell police |date=28 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently, a petition was filed by [[Law Society of Kenya]] claiming that the curfew itself was [[unconstitutional]], \"because it is blanket and indefinite, and because it is ultra vires [it contravenes] the Public Order Act\" and that the curfew posed a threat to the health of the general population. The petition further asserted that, \"police recklessly horded large crowds on the ground, contrary to WHO advice on social distancing. Moreover, the first respondent (police) stopped the media from monitoring their movement and assaulted journalists covering the process\". <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2001366258/lsk-wants-curfew-declared-illegal-or-delayed-to-10pm|website=www.standardmedia.co.ke|title=LSK wants curfew declared illegal or delayed to 10pm |date=30 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\nOn March 30, the [[High Court of Kenya]] upheld the curfew itself, but barred police from using excessive force to enforce the curfew  and demanded the police provide guidelines for observing the curfew. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2001366267/court-bars-police-from-using-excessive-force-during-curfew|website=www.standardmedia.co.ke|title=Court bars police from using excessive force during curfew|date=30 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, a 13-year-old boy was shot dead, allegedly by police, on the balcony of his home in Kiamaiko, Nairobi, 20 minutes after the curfew had started.<ref>{{cite web |title=Family distraught after teenager allegedly shot by police dies |url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Boy13-allegedly-shot-by-police-dies-/1056-5509816-c80fb8z/index.html |publisher=Daily Nation}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nThe travel restrictions reduced Kenya's hotel, tourism and [[Kenya Flower Council|flower]] industries. In contrast to citizens in [[Developed country|industrialized countries]], some Kenyans have the ability to switch from their city jobs to rural labour for food.<ref>{{cite web |title=#594 \u2014 The Economic Impact of Coronavirus on Kenya \u2013 Reports from Kenya |url=http://davidzarembka.com/2020/03/27/594-the-economic-impact-of-coronavirus-on-kenya/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328220959/http://davidzarembka.com/2020/03/27/594-the-economic-impact-of-coronavirus-on-kenya/ |archivedate=28 March 2020 |date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Kenya|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Kenya|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Kenya]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|Kenya]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Kenya]]\n", "name_user": "Young Kenyan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Kenya"}
{"title_page": "Mobile National Cemetery", "text_new": "{{container}}\n\n{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = Magnolia Cemetery including Mobile National Cemetery\n  | image = Mobile National Cemetery.JPG\n  | caption = A portion of Mobile National Cemetery.\n| coordinates = {{coord|30|40|22|N|88|03|45|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Alabama#USA\n  | location = [[Mobile, Alabama]]\n  | built = 1866\n  | architecture =\n  | added = 13 June 1986 <ref name= nris/>\n  | area = {{convert|91|acre}}\n  | governing_body = Local<!--National Cemetery Administration-->\n  | refnum = 86003757<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref><ref name=\"NRHP\">{{cite web|title=Alabama - Mobile County|work=\"Nationalhistoricalregister.com\"|\nurl=http://www.nationalhistoricalregister.com/al/Mobile/state2.html|accessdate=2007-11-18}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Mobile National Cemetery''' is a [[United States National Cemetery]] located in the city of [[Mobile, Alabama]]. It encompasses {{convert|5.2|acre}}, and as of the end of 2005, had 5,326 interments. It is an annex to the larger [[Magnolia Cemetery (Mobile, Alabama)|Magnolia Cemetery]].<ref name=\"sledge\">Sledge, John Sturdivant. ''Cities of Silence: A Guide to Mobile's Historic Cemeteries'', pages 24-26. Tuscaloosa, Alabama: University of Alabama Press, 2002.</ref>  Mobile National Cemetery is administered by [[Barrancas National Cemetery]] in [[Pensacola, Florida]], and is currently closed to new interments.<ref name=\"natcemetery\">{{cite web|title=Mobile National Cemetery|work=\"U.S. Department of Veteran Affairs\"|url=http://www.cem.va.gov/CEM/cems/nchp/mobile.asp#hi|accessdate=2007-11-27}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nMobile National Cemetery was established in 1865, when [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] troops occupied the city of Mobile after the [[Battle of Mobile Bay]], during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]].<ref name=\"natcemetery\"/>  Initially, casualties of the battle were interred in a section of the city owned [[Magnolia Cemetery (Mobile, Alabama)|Magnolia Cemetery]], but they quickly had a need for more space and a plot of {{convert|3|acre}} was granted to the [[United States Army|Army]] by the city in 1866.<ref name=\"natcemetery\"/>  By 1871, the cemetery had 841 interments, mostly soldiers whose remains were moved from other nearby battlefield sites.<ref name=\"natcemetery\"/>\n\nMobile National Cemetery was listed, along with the rest of [[Magnolia Cemetery (Mobile, Alabama)|Magnolia Cemetery]], on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on 13 June 1986.<ref name=nris/>\n\n== Notable monuments ==\n* The 76th Illinois Volunteer Infantry Regiment Monument was erected in 1892 by the survivors of the [[Battle of Fort Blakely]].<ref name=\"natcemetery\"/>\n* The Confederate Fortification Monument, a granite monument, was erected by the [[United Daughters of the Confederacy]] in 1940.<ref name=\"natcemetery\"/>\n\n== Notable interments ==\n* Private First Class [[John Dury New]], [[Medal of Honor]] recipient for action in [[World War II]].<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=UtGA-cP3-HsC&pg=PA211&lpg=PA211&dq=John+Dury+New+mobile+cemetery&source=bl&ots=Ehr0pJbi7Z&sig=ACfU3U25840PptUICpLyw1P6ezW8dWuMFw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj6soLZivjgAhVD2IMKHdn-ATYQ6AEwBXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=John%20Dury%20New%20mobile%20cemetery&f=false ''American Military Cemeteries'']</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.cem.va.gov/ National Cemetery Administration]\n* [http://www.cem.va.gov/CEM/cems/nchp/mobile.asp Mobile National Cemetery]\n* {{gnis|152201}}\n* [http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=cr&CRid=109427 Mobile National Cemetery] at [[Find a Grave]]\n* {{HALS |survey=AL-1 |id=al1321 |title=Mobile National Cemetery, 1202 Virginia Street, Mobile, Mobile County, AL |photos=38 |cap=4}}\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Mobile, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries on the National Register of Historic Places in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Historic American Landscapes Survey in Alabama]]\n[[Category:United States national cemeteries]]\n[[Category:1865 establishments in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in Mobile, Alabama]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = Magnolia Cemetery including Mobile National Cemetery\n  | image = Mobile National Cemetery.JPG\n  | caption = A portion of Mobile National Cemetery.\n| coordinates = {{coord|30|40|22|N|88|03|45|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Alabama#USA\n  | location = [[Mobile, Alabama]]\n  | built = 1866\n  | architecture =\n  | added = 13 June 1986 <ref name= nris/>\n  | area = {{convert|91|acre}}\n  | governing_body = Local<!--National Cemetery Administration-->\n  | refnum = 86003757<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref><ref name=\"NRHP\">{{cite web|title=Alabama - Mobile County|work=\"Nationalhistoricalregister.com\"|\nurl=http://www.nationalhistoricalregister.com/al/Mobile/state2.html|accessdate=2007-11-18}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Mobile National Cemetery''' is a [[United States National Cemetery]] located in the city of [[Mobile, Alabama]]. It encompasses {{convert|5.2|acre}}, and as of the end of 2005, had 5,326 interments. It is an annex to the larger [[Magnolia Cemetery (Mobile, Alabama)|Magnolia Cemetery]].<ref name=\"sledge\">Sledge, John Sturdivant. ''Cities of Silence: A Guide to Mobile's Historic Cemeteries'', pages 24-26. Tuscaloosa, Alabama: University of Alabama Press, 2002.</ref>  Mobile National Cemetery is administered by [[Barrancas National Cemetery]] in [[Pensacola, Florida]], and is currently closed to new interments.<ref name=\"natcemetery\">{{cite web|title=Mobile National Cemetery|work=\"U.S. Department of Veteran Affairs\"|url=http://www.cem.va.gov/CEM/cems/nchp/mobile.asp#hi|accessdate=2007-11-27}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nMobile National Cemetery was established in 1865, when [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] troops occupied the city of Mobile after the [[Battle of Mobile Bay]], during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]].<ref name=\"natcemetery\"/>  Initially, casualties of the battle were interred in a section of the city owned [[Magnolia Cemetery (Mobile, Alabama)|Magnolia Cemetery]], but they quickly had a need for more space and a plot of {{convert|3|acre}} was granted to the [[United States Army|Army]] by the city in 1866.<ref name=\"natcemetery\"/>  By 1871, the cemetery had 841 interments, mostly soldiers whose remains were moved from other nearby battlefield sites.<ref name=\"natcemetery\"/>\n\nMobile National Cemetery was listed, along with the rest of [[Magnolia Cemetery (Mobile, Alabama)|Magnolia Cemetery]], on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on 13 June 1986.<ref name=nris/>\n\n== Notable monuments ==\n* The 76th Illinois Volunteer Infantry Regiment Monument was erected in 1892 by the survivors of the [[Battle of Fort Blakely]].<ref name=\"natcemetery\"/>\n* The Confederate Fortification Monument, a granite monument, was erected by the [[United Daughters of the Confederacy]] in 1940.<ref name=\"natcemetery\"/>\n\n== Notable interments ==\n* Private First Class [[John Dury New]], [[Medal of Honor]] recipient for action in [[World War II]].<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=UtGA-cP3-HsC&pg=PA211&lpg=PA211&dq=John+Dury+New+mobile+cemetery&source=bl&ots=Ehr0pJbi7Z&sig=ACfU3U25840PptUICpLyw1P6ezW8dWuMFw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj6soLZivjgAhVD2IMKHdn-ATYQ6AEwBXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=John%20Dury%20New%20mobile%20cemetery&f=false ''American Military Cemeteries'']</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.cem.va.gov/ National Cemetery Administration]\n* [http://www.cem.va.gov/CEM/cems/nchp/mobile.asp Mobile National Cemetery]\n* {{gnis|152201}}\n* [http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=cr&CRid=109427 Mobile National Cemetery] at [[Find a Grave