oric party only|\n |color = #ADC\n |party =  [[Advance New Zealand]]\n |party votes = 6\n |party percent =0.03\n |party change = \n}}\n{{MMP election box historic party only|\n |color = #ABC\n |party = [[Superannuitants and Youth Action|Superannuitants & Youth]]\n |party votes = 6\n |party percent =0.03\n |party change = \n}}\n{{MMP election box historic party only|\n |color = #007\n |party = [[New Zealand Conservative Party|Conservatives]]\n |party votes = 4\n |party percent =0.02\n |party change = \n}}\n{{MMP election box party only|\n |party = Libertarianz\n |party votes = 3\n |party percent =0.01\n |party change = \n}}\n{{MMP election box historic party only|\n |color = #F93\n |party = [[Ethnic Minority Party of New Zealand|Ethnic Minority Party]]\n |party votes = 2\n |party percent =0.01\n |party change =\n}}\n{{MMP election box historic party only|\n |color = #3F9\n |party =  [[Asia Pacific United Party|Asia Pacific United]]\n |party votes = 0\n |party percent = 0.00\n |party change = \n}}\n{{MMP election box informal vote|\n |votes = 262\n |party votes = 235\n}}\n{{MMP election box total vote|\n |votes = 21,225\n |party votes = 21,252\n}}\n{{MMP election box majority win|\n |winner = New Zealand First\n |votes = 8,418\n |percent =39.66\n |change = \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{electorates of New Zealand}}\n\n[[Category:M\u0101ori electorates]]\n[[Category:1996 establishments in New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the M\u0101ori Anglican bishopric|Te P\u012bhopatanga o Te Tai Tokerau}}\n{{short description|Current New Zealand M\u0101ori electorate}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n[[File:Te Tai Tokerau electorate, 2014.svg|thumb|right|Te Tai Tokerau electorate boundaries used since the {{NZ election link|2002}}]]\n\n'''Te Tai Tokerau''' is a [[New Zealand]] parliamentary [[M\u0101ori electorates|M\u0101ori electorate]] that was created out of the [[Northern Maori]] electorate ahead of the first [[Mixed-member proportional representation|Mixed Member Proportional]] (MMP) election in [[1996 New Zealand general election|1996]]. It was first held by [[Tau Henare]] representing [[New Zealand First]] for one term, and then [[Dover Samuels]] of the [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour Party]] for two terms. From [[2005 New Zealand general election|2005]] to 2014, it was held by MP [[Hone Harawira]]. Initially a member of the [[M\u0101ori Party]], Harawira resigned from both the party and then Parliament, causing the [[2011 Te Tai Tokerau by-election|2011 by-election]]. He was returned under the [[Mana Party (New Zealand)|Mana Party]] banner in July 2011 and confirmed at the [[2011 New Zealand general election|November 2011 general election]]. In the {{NZ election link|2014}}, he was beaten by Labour's [[Kelvin Davis (politician)|Kelvin Davis]], ending the representation of the Mana Party in Parliament.\n\n== Population centres ==\nTe Tai Tokerau's boundaries are similar to those of the pre-[[Mixed-member proportional representation|Mixed Member Proportional]] (MMP) [[Northern Maori]] electorate. Te Tai Tokerau was created ahead of the first MMP [[1996 New Zealand general election|election in 1996]]. In the 2002 boundary redistribution, the size of the electorate shrank to make room for an increase in the number of M\u0101ori electorates from six to seven.<ref>{{cite book| title=Report of the Representation Commission 2002 |url= http://www.elections.org.nz/sites/default/files/2002%20Representation%20Commission%20Report.pdf |isbn=0-478-20169-9 |publisher=Representation Commission |accessdate=2 October 2014 |page=11 |format=PDF |date=21 March 2002}}</ref> The boundaries were not further altered in the 2007 or 2013/14 redistributions.<ref>{{cite book| title=Report of the Representation Commission 2007 |url= http://www.elections.org.nz/sites/default/files/2007%20Representation%20Commission%20Report.pdf |isbn=978-0-477-10414-2 |publisher=Representation Commission |accessdate=2 October 2014 |page=11 |format=PDF |date=14 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| title=Report of the Representation Commission 2014 |url= http://www.elections.org.nz/sites/default/files/bulk-upload/documents/report_of_the_representation_commission_2014.pdf |isbn=978-0-477-10414-2 |publisher=Representation Commission |accessdate=2 October 2014 |page=11 |format=PDF |date=4 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nTe Tai Tokerau is the northernmost [[M\u0101ori electorates|M\u0101ori electorate]], and covers an area between [[Cape Reinga]] in the [[Far North District|Far North]] of the [[North Island]] to a boundary cutting through West [[Auckland]]. The major population centres are [[Whangarei]], the [[Bay of Islands]] and north and west [[Auckland]]. The electorate contains all of the [[Ng\u0101puhi]], [[Te Aup\u014duri]], Ng\u0101ti Kuri, [[Te Rarawa]] and [[Ng\u0101ti Kahu]] tribal areas, and part of [[Ng\u0101ti Wh\u0101tua]]'s territory (''rohe'').\n\nIts analogous general electorates are {{NZ electorate link|East Coast Bays}}, {{NZ electorate link|North Shore}}, {{NZ electorate link|Northcote}}, {{NZ electorate link|Northland}}, {{NZ electorate link|Rodney}}, {{NZ electorate link|Te Atat\u016b}}, {{NZ electorate link|Upper Harbour}}, {{NZ electorate link|Whangarei}}, most of {{NZ electorate link|Helensville}}, part of {{NZ electorate link|Kelston}} and some of the islands located within {{NZ electorate link|Auckland Central}}.<ref name=\"Electorate boundaries\">{{cite web |title=Electorate Boundaries |url= http://www.elections.org.nz/voters/find-my-electorate |publisher=Elections New Zealand |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[Image:Whangarei Falls.jpg|thumb|right|[[Whangarei]]]]\n\nNorthern Maori had been held by the [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour Party]] since the [[1938 New Zealand general election|1938 election]], when longstanding [[Reform Party (New Zealand)|Reform]] MP [[Taurekareka Henare]] was beaten by Labour's [[Paraire Karaka Paikea]].<ref name=\"Scholefield 1950\">{{cite book |last= Scholefield |first= Guy |title= New Zealand Parliamentary Record, 1840\u20131949 |authorlink=Guy Scholefield |edition=3rd |origyear= First ed. published 1913 |year= 1950 |publisher=Govt. Printer |location= Wellington |page=131}}</ref> In 1993, after 55 years of his party holding the seat, Labour MP [[Bruce Gregory]] was beaten by Henare's great grandson, [[Tau Henare]], standing for [[New Zealand First]], ending Labour's unbroken hold on the four M\u0101ori seats. Henare went on to win Te Tai Tokerau after the switch to MMP, and New Zealand First won all five of the newly-drawn M\u0101ori electorates.\n\nAfter a tumultuous [[45th New Zealand Parliament|parliamentary term]] which saw all but one of the five New Zealand First M\u0101ori MPs defect to other parties, (including Henare himself, who went on to found [[Mauri Pacific]]), Labour won all six M\u0101ori electorates contested at the [[1999 New Zealand general election|1999 election]]. In Te Tai Tokerau, Tau Henare was beaten into third place behind the New Zealand First candidate and [[Dover Samuels]], who Henare had beaten three years previous.\n\nHowever, Labour's losing the five M\u0101ori electorates in 1996 showed that the M\u0101ori vote was contestable for the first time in five decades, as the new electoral system coupled with the rise of small parties meant that non-Labour candidacy in these seats was more feasible than under [[First Past the Post]].\n\nThe [[New Zealand foreshore and seabed controversy]] of 2004\u201305 proved to be the catalyst for the second challenge to Labour party domination of the M\u0101ori electorates, this time from the [[M\u0101ori Party]]. At the [[2005 New Zealand general election|2005 election]], Samuels and three other Labour M\u0101ori MPs lost their seats to M\u0101ori Party challengers. In Te Tai Tokerau, the winner was [[Hone Harawira]].<ref name=\"Harawira parliamentary bio\">{{cite web|title=Hone Harawira |url= http://www.parliament.nz/en-NZ/MPP/MPs/MPs/0/f/a/50MP126921-Harawira-Hone.htm |publisher=New Zealand Parliament |accessdate=3 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Te Tai Tokerau 2005 election\">{{cite web |title=Official Count Results \u2013 Te Tai Tokerau|url= http://www.electionresults.govt.nz/electionresults_2005/electorate-67.html |publisher=Chief Electoral Office, Wellington |accessdate=3 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nHarawira resigned from the M\u0101ori Party in early 2011 and became an independent MP. On 11 May 2011, he resigned from Parliament effective 20 May, seeking a mandate for his new party, the [[Mana Party (New Zealand)|Mana Party]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10724918 |title=Harawira resigns from Parliament |date=11 May 2011 |accessdate=11 May 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.elections.org.nz/voting/te-tai-tokerau-by-election/te-tai-tokerau-by-election-results.html ]{{dead link|date=December 2016}}</ref> This caused the 25 June 2011 [[2011 Te Tai Tokerau by-election|by-election]], which was contested by five parties, with the main contenders Harawira, [[Kelvin Davis (politician)|Kelvin Davis]] (Labour Party) and Solomon Tipene (M\u0101ori Party). Harawira retained the electorate with a majority of 1,117,<ref name=\"Te Tai Tokerau by-election 2011 results\">{{cite web |title=Official Count Results \u2013 Te Tai Tokerau |url= http://electionresults.govt.nz/2011_te_tai_tokerau_byelection/ |publisher=New Zealand Electoral Commission |accessdate=3 December 2011}}</ref> his previous majority being over 6,000.<ref name=\"Te Tai Tokerau 2008 election\">{{cite web|title=Official Count Results \u2013 Te Tai Tokerau |url= http://www.electionresults.govt.nz/electionresults_2008/electorate-68.html |publisher=Chief Electoral Office, Wellington |accessdate=3 December 2011}}</ref> In the [[2011 New Zealand general election|2011 general election]] some months later, Harawira had a similar majority to Davis.<ref name=\"2014 election\">{{cite web| url= http://electionresults.org.nz/electionresults_2014/electorate-69.html |title=Official Count Results \u2013 Te Tai Tokerau |publisher=[[Electoral Commission (New Zealand)|Electoral Commission]] |date=20 September 2014|accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Mana Party formed a [[coalition]] with the [[Internet Party (New Zealand)|Internet Party]] just prior to the [[2014 New Zealand general election]]. The coalition was registered with the [[Electoral Commission (New Zealand)|Electoral Commission]] as the [[Internet Party and Mana Movement]] in July 2014, allowing it to contest the party vote.<ref name=\"Internet MANA registration\">{{cite web |title=Registration of Internet Party and MANA Movement logo |url= http://www.elections.org.nz/news-media/registration-internet-party-and-mana-movement-logo |publisher=[[Electoral Commission (New Zealand)|Electoral Commission]] |date=24 July 2014 |accessdate=8 August 2014}}</ref> The Internet Party was founded by controversial online millionaire [[Kim Dotcom]], and this strategic coalition resulted in Harawira's main opponent, Labour's Kelvin Davis, getting endorsements from [[Winston Peters]] of [[New Zealand First]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bennett |first1=Adam |title=Election 2014: Winston Peters hits out at National after big poll surge |url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11328639 |accessdate=3 October 2014 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=21 September 2014}}</ref> and the Prime Minister, [[John Key]] of the [[New Zealand National Party|National Party]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=McQuillan|first1=Laura|title=Key's subtle endorsement for Kelvin Davis|url=http://www.newstalkzb.co.nz/auckland/election/news/83283426-key-s-subtle-endorsement-for-kelvin-davis|accessdate=3 October 2014|work=[[Newstalk ZB]]|date=17 September 2014}}</ref> Even the electorate's candidate for the [[M\u0101ori Party]], Te Hira Paenga, reminded voters of the importance of strategic voting.<ref>{{cite news |title=Davis picking up endorsements |url= http://www.waateanews.com/waateanews/x_story_id/NzkxNg==/Davis-picking-up-endorsements |accessdate=3 October 2014 |work=Radio Waatea |date=19 September 2014}}</ref> In his fourth challenge in the Te Tai Tokerau electorate, Davis ousted the incumbent Harawira, which ended the representation of the Mana Party in Parliament.<ref name=\"Ousted Harawira\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Simon |title=Davis' win a critical blow for Harawira, Internet Mana |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/10524510/Davis-win-a-critical-blow-for-Harawira-Internet-Mana |accessdate=30 September 2014 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=20 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Members of Parliament===\n'''Key'''\n\n{{Party index link|New Zealand First}}\n{{Party index link|New Zealand Labour Party}}\n{{Party index link|M\u0101ori Party}}\n{{Party index link|Mana Party (New Zealand)}}\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!width=100| Election\n! style=\"width:175px;\" colspan=\"2\"| Winner\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|1996}}\n| width=5 bgcolor={{New Zealand First/meta/color}}|\n| [[Tau Henare]]\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|1999}}\n| rowspan=2 bgcolor={{New Zealand Labour Party/meta/color}}|\n| rowspan=2 | [[Dover Samuels]]\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|2002}}\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|2005}}\n| rowspan=2 bgcolor={{M\u0101ori Party/meta/color}}|\n| rowspan=4 | [[Hone Harawira]]\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|2008}}\n|-\n|{{By-election link small|Te Tai Tokerau|2011}}\n| rowspan=2 bgcolor={{Mana Party (New Zealand)/meta/color}}|\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|2011}}\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|2014}}\n| rowspan=2 bgcolor={{New Zealand Labour Party/meta/color}}|\n| rowspan=2| [[Kelvin Davis (politician)|Kelvin Davis]]\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|2017}}\n|}\n\n===List MPs===\nMembers of Parliament elected from party lists in elections where that person also unsuccessfully contested Te Tai Tokerau. Unless otherwise stated, all MPs terms began and ended at general elections.\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!width=10